# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mri-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In **diffusion weighted imaging** (DWI), the intensity of each image element (voxel) reflects the best estimate of the rate of water diffusion at that location.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Because the mobility of water is driven by thermal agitation and highly dependent on its cellular environment, the hypothesis behind DWI is that findings may indicate (early) pathologic change.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] For instance, DWI is more sensitive to early changes after a stroke than more traditional MRI measurements such as T1 or T2 relaxation rates.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion-weighted images are very useful to diagnose vascular strokes in the brain.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] It is also used more and more in the staging of non-small-cell lung cancer, where it is a serious candidate to replace positron emission tomography as the 'gold standard' for this type of disease.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion tensor imaging is being developed for studying the diseases of the white matter of the brain as well as for studies of other body tissues (see below).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] DWI is most applicable when the tissue of interest is dominated by isotropic water movement e.g. grey matter in the cerebral cortex and major brain nuclei, or in the body—where the diffusion rate appears to be the same when measured along any axis.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] However, DWI also remains sensitive to T1 and T2 relaxation.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] To entangle diffusion and relaxation effects on image contrast, one may obtain quantitative images of the diffusion coefficient, or more exactly the apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The ADC concept was introduced to take into account the fact that the diffusion process is complex in biological tissues and reflects several different mechanisms.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Traditionally, in diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI), three gradient-directions are applied, sufficient to estimate the trace of the diffusion tensor or 'average diffusivity', a putative measure of edema.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Clinically, trace-weighted images have proven to be very useful to diagnose vascular strokes in the brain, by early detection (within a couple of minutes) of the hypoxic edema.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] More extended DTI scans derive neural tract directional information from the data using 3D or multidimensional vector algorithms based on six or more gradient directions, sufficient to compute the diffusion tensor.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The diffusion tensor model is a rather simple model of the diffusion process, assuming homogeneity and linearity of the diffusion within each image voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] From the diffusion tensor, diffusion anisotropy measures such as the fractional anisotropy (FA), can be computed.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Moreover, the principal direction of the diffusion tensor can be used to infer the white-matter connectivity of the brain (i.e. tractography; trying to see which part of the brain is connected to which other part).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] More advanced models of the diffusion process have been proposed that aim to overcome the weaknesses of the diffusion tensor model.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Amongst others, these include q-space imaging and generalized diffusion tensor imaging.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion imaging is an MRI method that produces in vivo magnetic resonance images of biological tissues sensitized with the local characteristics of molecular diffusion, generally water (but other moieties can also be investigated using MR spectroscopic approaches).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] MRI can be made sensitive to the motion of molecules.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Regular MRI acquisition utilizes the behavior of protons in water to generate contrast between clinically relevant features of a particular subject.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The versatile nature of MRI is due to this capability of producing contrast related to the structure of tissues at the microscopic level.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In a typical T1-weighted image, water molecules in a sample are excited with the imposition of a strong magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This causes many of the protons in water molecules to precess simultaneously, producing signals in MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In T2-weighted images, contrast is produced by measuring the loss of coherence or synchrony between the water protons.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] When water is in an environment where it can freely tumble, relaxation tends to take longer.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In certain clinical situations, this can generate contrast between an area of pathology and the surrounding healthy tissue.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] To sensitize MRI images to diffusion, the magnetic field strength (B1) is varied linearly by a pulsed field gradient.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Since precession is proportional to the magnet strength, the protons begin to precess at different rates, resulting in dispersion of the phase and signal loss.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Another gradient pulse is applied in the same magnitude but with opposite direction to refocus or rephase the spins.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The refocusing will not be perfect for protons that have moved during the time interval between the pulses, and the signal measured by the MRI machine is reduced.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This combination is not trivial, as cross-terms arise between all gradient pulses.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The equation set by Stejskal and Tanner then becomes inaccurate and the signal attenuation must be calculated, either analytically or numerically, integrating all gradient pulses present in the MRI sequence and their interactions.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] At the end, images are "weighted" by the diffusion process: In those diffusion-weighted images (DWI) the signal is more attenuated the faster the diffusion and the larger the b factor is.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] However, those diffusion-weighted images are still also sensitive to T1 and T2 relaxivity contrast, which can sometimes be confusing.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Although this ADC concept has been extremely successful, especially for clinical applications, it has been challenged recently, as new, more comprehensive models of diffusion in biological tissues have been introduced.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Those models have been made necessary, as diffusion in tissues is not free.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In this condition, the ADC seems to depend on the choice of b values (the ADC seems to decrease when using larger b values), as the plot of ln(S/So) is not linear with the b factor, as expected from the above equations.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This deviation from a free diffusion behavior is what makes diffusion MRI so successful, as the ADC is very sensitive to changes in tissue microstructure.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] On the other hand, modeling diffusion in tissues is becoming very complex.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Among most popular models are the biexponential model, which assumes the presence of 2 water pools in slow or intermediate exchange and the cumulant-expansion (also called Kurtosis) model, which does not necessarily require the presence of 2 pools.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] which has terms for precession, T2 relaxation, and T1 relaxation.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Torrey mathematically showed how the Bloch equations for magnetization would change with the addition of diffusion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Torrey modified Bloch's original description of transverse magnetization to include diffusion terms and the application of a spatially varying gradient.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Since the magnetization M is a vector, there are 3 diffusion equations, one for each dimension.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] where ${\vec {D}}$ is now the diffusion tensor.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The exponential term will be referred to as the *attenuation* A .
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Anisotropic diffusion will have a similar solution for the diffusion tensor, except that what will be measured is the *apparent diffusion coefficient* (ADC).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] where the $b_{ij}$ terms incorporate the gradient fields $G_{x}$ , $G_{y}$ , and $G_{z}$ .
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The standard grayscale of DWI images is to represent increased diffusion restriction as brighter.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] An *apparent diffusion coefficient* (ADC) image, or an *ADC map*, is an MRI image that more specifically shows diffusion than conventional DWI, by eliminating the T2 weighting that is otherwise inherent to conventional DWI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] ADC imaging does so by acquiring multiple conventional DWI images with different amounts of DWI weighting, and the change in signal is proportional to the rate of diffusion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Contrary to DWI images, the standard grayscale of ADC images is to represent a smaller magnitude of diffusion as darker.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Cerebral infarction leads to diffusion restriction, and the difference between images with various DWI weighting will therefore be minor, leading to an ADC image with low signal in the infarcted area.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] A decreased ADC may be detected minutes after a cerebral infarction.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The high signal of infarcted tissue on conventional DWI is a result of its partial T2 weighting.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] It also provides useful structural information about muscle—including heart muscle—as well as other tissues such as the prostate.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In DTI, each voxel has one or more pairs of parameters: a rate of diffusion and a preferred direction of diffusion—described in terms of three-dimensional space—for which that parameter is valid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The properties of each voxel of a single DTI image are usually calculated by vector or tensor math from six or more different diffusion weighted acquisitions, each obtained with a different orientation of the diffusion sensitizing gradients.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In some methods, hundreds of measurements—each making up a complete image—are made to generate a single resulting calculated image data set.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The higher information content of a DTI voxel makes it extremely sensitive to subtle pathology in the brain.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In addition the directional information can be exploited at a higher level of structure to select and follow neural tracts through the brain—a process called tractography.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] A more precise statement of the image acquisition process is that the image-intensities at each position are attenuated, depending on the strength (*b*-value) and direction of the so-called magnetic diffusion gradient, as well as on the local microstructure in which the water molecules diffuse.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The more attenuated the image is at a given position, the greater diffusion there is in the direction of the diffusion gradient.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In order to measure the tissue's complete diffusion profile, one needs to repeat the MR scans, applying different directions (and possibly strengths) of the diffusion gradient for each scan.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion MRI relies on the mathematics and physical interpretations of the geometric quantities known as tensors.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Only a special case of the general mathematical notion is relevant to imaging, which is based on the concept of a symmetric matrix.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Tensors have a real, physical existence in a material or tissue so that they do not move when the coordinate system used to describe them is rotated.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] There are numerous different possible representations of a tensor (of rank 2), but among these, this discussion focuses on the ellipsoid because of its physical relevance to diffusion and because of its historical significance in the development of diffusion anisotropy imaging in MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The same matrix of numbers can have a simultaneous second use to describe the shape and orientation of an ellipse and the same matrix of numbers can be used simultaneously in a third way for matrix mathematics to sort out eigenvectors and eigenvalues as explained below.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The idea of a tensor in physical science evolved from attempts to describe the quantity of physical properties.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The first properties they were applied to were those that can be described by a single number, such as temperature.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Properties that can be described this way are called scalars; these can be considered tensors of rank 0, or 0th-order tensors.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Tensors can also be used to describe quantities that have directionality, such as mechanical force.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] These quantities require specification of both magnitude and direction, and are often represented with a vector.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] A three-dimensional vector can be described with three components: its projection on the *x,* *y*, and *z* axes.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Vectors of this sort can be considered tensors of rank 1, or 1st-order tensors.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] A tensor is often a physical or biophysical property that determines the relationship between two vectors.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] When a force is applied to an object, movement can result.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] If the movement is in a single direction, the transformation can be described using a vector—a tensor of rank 1.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] However, in a tissue, diffusion leads to movement of water molecules along trajectories that proceed along multiple directions over time, leading to a complex projection onto the Cartesian axes.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This pattern is reproducible if the same conditions and forces are applied to the same tissue in the same way.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] If there is an internal anisotropic organization of the tissue that constrains diffusion, then this fact will be reflected in the pattern of diffusion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The relationship between the properties of driving force that generate diffusion of the water molecules and the resulting pattern of their movement in the tissue can be described by a tensor.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The collection of molecular displacements of this physical property can be described with nine components—each one associated with a pair of axes *xx*, *yy*, *zz*, *xy*, *yx*, *xz*, *zx*, *yz*, *zy*.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] These can be written as a matrix similar to the one at the start of this section.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion from a point source in the anisotropic medium of white matter behaves in a similar fashion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The first pulse of the Stejskal Tanner diffusion gradient effectively labels some water molecules and the second pulse effectively shows their displacement due to diffusion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Each gradient direction applied measures the movement along the direction of that gradient.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Six or more gradients are summed to get all the measurements needed to fill in the matrix, assuming it is symmetric above and below the diagonal (red subscripts).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In 1848, Henri Hureau de Sénarmont applied a heated point to a polished crystal surface that had been coated with wax.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In some materials that had "isotropic" structure, a ring of melt would spread across the surface in a circle.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In anisotropic crystals the spread took the form of an ellipse.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In three dimensions this spread is an ellipsoid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] As Adolf Fick showed in the 1850s, diffusion exhibits many of the same patterns as those seen in the transfer of heat.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] At this point, it is helpful to consider the mathematics of ellipsoids.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] An ellipsoid can be described by the formula: $ax^{2}+by^{2}+cz^{2}=1$ .
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This equation describes a quadric surface.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The relative values of *a*, *b*, and *c* determine if the quadric describes an ellipsoid or a hyperboloid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] As it turns out, three more components can be added as follows: $ax^{2}+by^{2}+cz^{2}+dyz+ezx+fxy=1$ .
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Many combinations of *a*, *b*, *c*, *d*, *e*, and *f* still describe ellipsoids, but the additional components (*d*, *e*, *f*) describe the rotation of the ellipsoid relative to the orthogonal axes of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This is what is meant when it is stated that a second-order symmetric tensor can be represented by an ellipsoid—if the diffusion values of the six terms of the quadric ellipsoid are placed into the matrix, this generates an ellipsoid angled off the orthogonal grid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Its shape will be more elongated if the relative anisotropy is high.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Mathematically, the diffusion matrix ⁠ ${\bar {D}}$ ⁠ is a covariance matrix.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The ellipsoid that shows the pattern of dispersion is given by the equation ⁠ ${\vec {v}}^{T}{\bar {D}}^{-1}v=1$ ⁠, where ⁠ ${\vec {v}}$ ⁠ is displacement, the column vector ⁠ $(x,y,z)^{T}$ ⁠.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] When the ellipsoid/tensor is represented by a matrix, we can apply a useful technique from standard matrix mathematics and linear algebra—that is to "diagonalize" the matrix.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This has two important meanings in imaging.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The idea is that there are two equivalent ellipsoids—of identical shape but with different size and orientation.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The first one is the measured diffusion ellipsoid sitting at an angle determined by the axons, and the second one is perfectly aligned with the three Cartesian axes.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The term "diagonalize" refers to the three components of the matrix along a diagonal from upper left to lower right (the components with red subscripts in the matrix at the start of this section).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The variables $ax^{2}$ , $by^{2}$ , and $cz^{2}$ are along the diagonal (red subscripts), but the variables *d*, *e* and *f* are "off diagonal".
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] It then becomes possible to do a vector processing step in which we rewrite our matrix and replace it with a new matrix multiplied by three different vectors of unit length (length=1.0).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The matrix is diagonalized because the off-diagonal components are all now zero.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The rotation angles required to get to this equivalent position now appear in the three vectors and can be read out as the *x*, *y*, and *z* components of each of them.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Those three vectors are called "eigenvectors" or characteristic vectors.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] They contain the orientation information of the original ellipsoid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The three axes of the ellipsoid are now directly along the main orthogonal axes of the coordinate system so we can easily infer their lengths.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] These lengths are the eigenvalues or characteristic values.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The second matrix provides eigenvector information.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In present-day clinical neurology, various brain pathologies may be best detected by looking at particular measures of anisotropy and diffusivity.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The underlying physical process of diffusion causes a group of water molecules to move out from a central point, and gradually reach the surface of an ellipsoid if the medium is anisotropic (it would be the surface of a sphere for an isotropic medium).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The ellipsoid formalism functions also as a mathematical method of organizing tensor data.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Measurement of an ellipsoid tensor further permits a retrospective analysis, to gather information about the process of diffusion in each voxel of the tissue.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In an isotropic medium such as cerebrospinal fluid, water molecules are moving due to diffusion and they move at equal rates in all directions.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] By knowing the detailed effects of diffusion gradients we can generate a formula that allows us to convert the signal attenuation of an MRI voxel into a numerical measure of diffusion—the diffusion coefficient *D*.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The ADC in anisotropic tissue varies depending on the direction in which it is measured.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Diffusion is fast along the length of (parallel to) an axon, and slower perpendicularly across it.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Once we have measured the voxel from six or more directions and corrected for attenuations due to T2 and T1 effects, we can use information from our calculated ellipsoid tensor to describe what is happening in the voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] If you consider an ellipsoid sitting at an angle in a Cartesian grid then you can consider the projection of that ellipse onto the three axes.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The three projections can give you the ADC along each of the three axes ADC*x*, ADC*y*, ADC*z*.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We use the *i* subscript to signify that this is what the isotropic diffusion coefficient would be with the effects of anisotropy averaged out.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The ellipsoid itself has a principal long axis and then two more small axes that describe its width and depth.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] All three of these are perpendicular to each other and cross at the center point of the ellipsoid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We call the axes in this setting **eigenvectors** and the measures of their lengths **eigenvalues**.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The lengths are symbolized by the Greek letter *λ*.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The long one pointing along the axon direction will be *λ*1 and the two small axes will have lengths *λ*2 and *λ*3.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In the setting of the DTI tensor ellipsoid, we can consider each of these as a measure of the diffusivity along each of the three primary axes of the ellipsoid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This is a little different from the ADC since that was a projection on the axis, while *λ* is an actual measurement of the ellipsoid we have calculated.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The diffusivity along the principal axis, *λ*1 is also called the longitudinal diffusivity or the **axial diffusivity** or even the parallel diffusivity *λ*∥.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Historically, this is closest to what Richards originally measured with the vector length in 1991.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This quantity is an assessment of the degree of restriction due to membranes and other effects and proves to be a sensitive measure of degenerative pathology in some neurological conditions.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] It can also be called the perpendicular diffusivity ( $\lambda _{\perp }$ ).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] $\mathrm {tr} (\Lambda )=\lambda _{1}+\lambda _{2}+\lambda _{3}$ where $\Lambda$ is a diagonal matrix with eigenvalues $\lambda _{1}$ , $\lambda _{2}$ and $\lambda _{3}$ on its diagonal.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] which equals *ADCi* since ${\begin{aligned}\mathrm {tr} (\Lambda )/3&=\mathrm {tr} (V^{-1}V\Lambda )/3\\&=\mathrm {tr} (V\Lambda V^{-1})/3\\&=\mathrm {tr} (D)/3\\&=ADC_{i}\end{aligned}}$ where V is the matrix of eigenvectors and D is the diffusion tensor.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Aside from describing the amount of diffusion, it is often important to describe the relative degree of anisotropy in a voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] At one extreme would be the sphere of isotropic diffusion and at the other extreme would be a cigar or pencil shaped very thin prolate spheroid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The simplest measure is obtained by dividing the longest axis of the ellipsoid by the shortest = (*λ*1/*λ*3).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] However, this proves to be very susceptible to measurement noise, so increasingly complex measures were developed to capture the measure while minimizing the noise.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] An important element of these calculations is the sum of squares of the diffusivity differences = (*λ*1 − *λ*2)2 + (*λ*1 − *λ*3)2 + (*λ*2 − *λ*3)2.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We use the square root of the sum of squares to obtain a sort of weighted average—dominated by the largest component.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] One objective is to keep the number near 0 if the voxel is spherical but near 1 if it is elongate.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This leads to the **fractional anisotropy** or **FA** which is the square root of the sum of squares (SRSS) of the diffusivity differences, divided by the SRSS of the diffusivities.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] When the second and third axes are small relative to the principal axis, the number in the numerator is almost equal the number in the denominator.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We also multiply by $1/{\sqrt {2}}$ so that FA has a maximum value of 1.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The fractional anisotropy can also be separated into linear, planar, and spherical measures depending on the "shape" of the diffusion ellipsoid.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] For example, a "cigar" shaped prolate ellipsoid indicates a strongly linear anisotropy, a "flying saucer" or oblate spheroid represents diffusion in a plane, and a sphere is indicative of isotropic diffusion, equal in all directions.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Each measure lies between 0 and 1 and they sum to unity.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The most common application of conventional DWI (without DTI) is in acute brain ischemia.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] DWI directly visualizes the ischemic necrosis in cerebral infarction in the form of a cytotoxic edema, appearing as a high DWI signal within minutes of arterial occlusion.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] With perfusion MRI detecting both the infarcted core and the salvageable penumbra, the latter can be quantified by DWI and perfusion MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Another application area of DWI is in oncology.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Tumors are in many instances highly cellular, giving restricted diffusion of water, and therefore appear with a relatively high signal intensity in DWI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] DWI is commonly used to detect and stage tumors, and also to monitor tumor response to treatment over time.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] DWI can also be collected to visualize the whole body using a technique called 'diffusion-weighted whole-body imaging with background body signal suppression' (DWIBS).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Some more specialized diffusion MRI techniques such as diffusion kurtosis imaging (DKI) have also been shown to predict the response of cancer patients to chemotherapy treatment.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The principal application is in the imaging of white matter where the location, orientation, and anisotropy of the tracts can be measured.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The architecture of the axons in parallel bundles, and their myelin sheaths, facilitate the diffusion of the water molecules preferentially along their main direction.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Such preferentially oriented diffusion is called **anisotropic diffusion**.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The imaging of this property is an extension of diffusion MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The fiber direction is indicated by the tensor's main eigenvector.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This vector can be color-coded, yielding a cartography of the tracts' position and direction (red for left-right, blue for superior-inferior, and green for anterior-posterior).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The brightness is weighted by the fractional anisotropy which is a scalar measure of the degree of anisotropy in a given voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Mean diffusivity (MD) or trace is a scalar measure of the total diffusion within a voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] These measures are commonly used clinically to localize white matter lesions that do not show up on other forms of clinical MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Early in the development of DTI based tractography, a number of researchers pointed out a flaw in the diffusion tensor model.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The tensor analysis assumes that there is a single ellipsoid in each imaging voxel—as if all of the axons traveling through a voxel traveled in exactly the same direction.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This is often true, but it can be estimated that in more than 30% of the voxels in a standard resolution brain image, there are at least two different neural tracts traveling in different directions that pass through each other.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In the classic diffusion ellipsoid tensor model, the information from the crossing tract appears as noise or unexplained decreased anisotropy in a given voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] David Tuch was among the first to describe a solution to this problem.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The idea is best understood by conceptually placing a kind of geodesic dome around each image voxel.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This icosahedron provides a mathematical basis for passing a large number of evenly spaced gradient trajectories through the voxel—each coinciding with one of the apices of the icosahedron.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We can then look into the voxel from a large number of different directions (typically 40 or more).
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We use "*n*-tuple" tessellations to add more evenly spaced apices to the original icosahedron (20 faces)—an idea that also had its precedents in paleomagnetism research several decades earlier.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] We want to know which direction lines turn up the maximum anisotropic diffusion measures.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] If there is a single tract, there will be only two maxima, pointing in opposite directions.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] If two tracts cross in the voxel, there will be two pairs of maxima, and so on.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] The Q-Ball method of tractography is an implementation in which David Tuch provides a mathematical alternative to the tensor model.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Instead of forcing the diffusion anisotropy data into a group of tensors, the mathematics used deploys both probability distributions and some classic geometric tomography and vector mathematics developed nearly 100 years ago—the Funk Radon Transform.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Note, there is ongoing debate about the best way to preprocess DW-MRI.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Several in-vivo studies have shown that the choice of software and functions applied (directed at correcting artefacts arising from e.g. motion and eddy-currents) have a meaningful impact on the DTI parameter estimates from tissue.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Consequently, this is the topic of a multinational study directed by the diffusion-study group of the ISMRM.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] For DTI, it is generally possible to use linear algebra, matrix mathematics and vector mathematics to process the analysis of the tensor data.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] In some cases, the full set of tensor properties is of interest, but for tractography it is usually necessary to know only the magnitude and orientation of the primary axis or vector.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] This primary axis—the one with the greatest length—is the largest eigenvalue and its orientation is encoded in its matched eigenvector.
[src:mri-physics/diffusion-mri] Only one axis is needed as it is assumed the largest eigenvalue is aligned with the main axon direction to accomplish tractography.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The primary form of fMRI uses the blood-oxygen-level dependent (BOLD) contrast, discovered by Seiji Ogawa and his colleagues in 1990.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is a type of specialized brain and body scan used to map neural activity in the brain or spinal cord of humans or other animals by imaging the change in blood flow (hemodynamic response) related to energy use by nerve cells.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since the early 1990s, fMRI has come to dominate brain mapping research because it is noninvasive, typically requiring no injections, surgery, or the ingestion of substances such as radioactive tracers as in positron emission tomography.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Data acquired using fMRI, however, is frequently corrupted by noise from various sources; hence, statistical procedures are used to extract the underlying signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The resulting brain activation can be graphically represented by color-coding the strength of activation across the brain or the specific region studied.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The technique can localize activity to within millimeters but, using standard techniques, no better than within a window of a few seconds.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Other methods of obtaining contrast are arterial spin labeling and diffusion MRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Diffusion MRI is similar to BOLD fMRI but provides contrast based on the magnitude of diffusion of water molecules in the brain.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In addition to detecting BOLD responses from activity due to tasks or stimuli, fMRI can measure resting state, or negative-task state, which shows the subjects' baseline BOLD variance.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since about 1998 studies have shown the existence and properties of the default mode network, a functionally connected neural network of apparent *resting brain states*.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] fMRI is used in research, and to a lesser extent, in clinical work.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It can complement other measures of brain physiology such as electroencephalography (EEG), and near-infrared spectroscopy (NIRS).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Newer methods which improve both spatial and time resolution are being researched, and these largely use biomarkers other than the BOLD signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Some companies have developed commercial products such as lie detectors based on fMRI techniques, but the research is not believed to be developed enough for widespread commercial use.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The fMRI concept builds on the earlier MRI scanning technology and the discovery of properties of oxygen-rich blood.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] MRI brain scans use a strong, uniform, static magnetic field to align the spins of nuclei in the brain region being studied.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Another magnetic field, with a gradient strength rather than a uniform one, is then applied to spatially distinguish different nuclei.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Finally, a radiofrequency (RF) pulse is applied to flip the nuclear spins, with the effect depending on where they are located, due to the gradient field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] After the RF pulse, the nuclei return to their original (equilibrium) spin populations, and the energy they emit is measured with a coil.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The use of the gradient field allows the positions of the nuclei to be determined.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] MRI thus provides a static structural view of brain matter.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The central thrust behind fMRI was to extend MRI to capture functional changes in the brain caused by neuronal activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Differences in magnetic properties between arterial (oxygen-rich) and venous (oxygen-poor) blood provided this link.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since the 1890s, it has been known that changes in blood flow and blood oxygenation in the brain (collectively known as brain hemodynamics) are closely linked to neural activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] When neurons become active, local blood flow to those brain regions increases, and oxygen-rich (oxygenated) blood displaces oxygen-depleted (deoxygenated) blood around 2 seconds later.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This rises to a peak over 4–6 seconds, before falling back to the original level (and typically undershooting slightly).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Oxygen is carried by the hemoglobin molecule in red blood cells.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Deoxygenated hemoglobin (dHb) is more magnetic (paramagnetic) than oxygenated hemoglobin (Hb), which is virtually resistant to magnetism (diamagnetic).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This difference leads to an improved MR signal since the diamagnetic blood interferes with the magnetic MR signal less.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This improvement can be mapped to show which neurons are active at a time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] first noted that dried blood is not magnetic and "Must try recent fluid blood." in diary dated 8th November 1845.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This was cited in Pauling & Coryell (1945).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] During the late 19th century, Angelo Mosso invented the 'human circulation balance', which could non-invasively measure the redistribution of blood during emotional and intellectual activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] However, although briefly mentioned by William James in 1890, the details and precise workings of this balance and the experiments Mosso performed with it remained largely unknown until the recent discovery of the original instrument as well as Mosso's reports by Stefano Sandrone and colleagues.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Angelo Mosso investigated several critical variables that are still relevant in modern neuroimaging such as the 'signal-to-noise ratio', the appropriate choice of the experimental paradigm and the need for the simultaneous recording of differing physiological parameters.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In 1890, Charles Roy and Charles Sherrington first experimentally linked brain function to its blood flow, at Cambridge University.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Seiji Ogawa at AT&T Bell labs recognized that this could be used to augment MRI, which could study just the static structure of the brain, since the differing magnetic properties of dHb and Hb caused by blood flow to activated brain regions would cause measurable changes in the MRI signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] BOLD is the MRI contrast of dHb, discovered in 1990 by Ogawa.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In a seminal 1990 study based on earlier work by Thulborn et al., Ogawa and colleagues scanned rodents in a strong magnetic field (7.0 T) MRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To manipulate blood oxygen level, they changed the proportion of oxygen the animals breathed.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] As this proportion fell, a map of blood flow in the brain was seen in the MRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] They verified this by placing test tubes with oxygenated or deoxygenated blood and creating separate images.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] They also showed that gradient-echo images, which depend on a form of loss of magnetization called T2* decay, produced the best images.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To show these blood flow changes were related to functional brain activity, they changed the composition of the air breathed by rats, and scanned them while monitoring brain activity with EEG.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The first attempt to detect the regional brain activity using MRI was performed by Belliveau and colleagues at Harvard University using the contrast agent Magnevist, a paramagnetic substance remaining in the bloodstream after intravenous injection.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] However, this method is not popular in human fMRI, because of the inconvenience of the contrast agent injection, and because the agent stays in the blood only for a short time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Three studies in 1992 were the first to explore using the BOLD contrast in humans.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Kenneth Kwong and colleagues, using both gradient-echo and inversion recovery echo-planar imaging (EPI) sequence at a magnetic field strength of 1.5 T published studies showing clear activation of the human visual cortex.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The Harvard team thereby showed that both blood flow and blood volume increased locally in activity neural tissue.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] T2* decay is caused by magnetized nuclei in a volume of space losing magnetic coherence (transverse magnetization) from both bumping into one another and from experiencing differences in the magnetic field strength across locations (field inhomogeneity from a spatial gradient).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Bandettini and colleagues used EPI at 1.5 T to show activation in the primary motor cortex, a brain area at the last stage of the circuitry controlling voluntary movements.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The magnetic fields, pulse sequences and procedures and techniques used by these early studies are still used in current-day fMRI studies.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But today researchers typically collect data from more slices (using stronger magnetic gradients), and preprocess and analyze data using statistical techniques.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The brain does not store a lot of glucose, its primary source of energy.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] When neurons become active, getting them back to their original state of polarization requires actively pumping ions across the neuronal cell membranes, in both directions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The energy for those ion pumps is mainly produced from glucose.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] More blood flows in to transport more glucose, also bringing in more oxygen in the form of oxygenated hemoglobin molecules in red blood cells.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is from both a higher rate of blood flow and an expansion of blood vessels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The blood-flow change is localized to within 2 or 3 mm of where the neural activity is.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Usually the brought-in oxygen is more than the oxygen consumed in burning glucose (it is not yet settled whether most glucose consumption is oxidative), and this causes a net decrease in deoxygenated hemoglobin (dHb) in that brain area's blood vessels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This changes the magnetic property of the blood, making it interfere less with the magnetization and its eventual decay induced by the MRI process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The cerebral blood flow (CBF) corresponds to the consumed glucose differently in different brain regions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Initial results show there is more inflow than consumption of glucose in regions such as the amygdala, basal ganglia, thalamus and cingulate cortex, all of which are recruited for fast responses.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In regions that are more deliberative, such as the lateral frontal and lateral parietal lobes, it seems that incoming flow is less than consumption.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Hemoglobin differs in how it responds to magnetic fields, depending on whether it has a bound oxygen molecule.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The dHb molecule is more attracted to magnetic fields.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Hence, it distorts the surrounding magnetic field induced by an MRI scanner, causing the nuclei there to lose magnetization faster via the T2* decay.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Thus MR pulse sequences sensitive to T2* show more MR signal where blood is highly oxygenated and less where it is not.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This effect increases with the square of the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The fMRI signal hence needs both a strong magnetic field (1.5 T or higher) and a pulse sequence such as EPI, which is sensitive to T2* contrast.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The physiological blood-flow response largely decides the temporal sensitivity, that is how accurately we can measure when neurons are active, in BOLD fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The basic time resolution parameter (sampling time) is designated TR; the TR dictates how often a particular brain slice is excited and allowed to lose its magnetization.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] TRs could vary from the very short (500 ms) to the very long (3 s).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] For fMRI specifically, the hemodynamic response lasts over 10 seconds, rising multiplicatively (that is, as a proportion of current value), peaking at 4 to 6 seconds, and then falling multiplicatively.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Changes in the blood-flow system, the vascular system, integrate responses to neuronal activity over time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Because this response is a smooth continuous function, sampling with ever-faster TRs does not help; it just gives more points on the response curve obtainable by simple linear interpolation anyway.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Experimental paradigms such as staggering when a stimulus is presented at various trials can improve temporal resolution, but reduces the number of effective data points obtained.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The change in the MR signal from neuronal activity is called the hemodynamic response (HR).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It lags the neuronal events triggering it by a couple of seconds, since it takes a while for the vascular system to respond to the brain's need for glucose.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] From this point it typically rises to a peak at about 5 seconds after the stimulus.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] If the neurons keep firing, say from a continuous stimulus, the peak spreads to a flat plateau while the neurons stay active.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] After activity stops, the BOLD signal falls below the original level, the baseline, a phenomenon called the undershoot.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Over time the signal recovers to the baseline.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] There is some evidence that continuous metabolic requirements in a brain region contribute to the undershoot.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The mechanism by which the neural system provides feedback to the vascular system of its need for more glucose is partly the release of glutamate as part of neuron firing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This glutamate affects nearby supporting cells, astrocytes, causing a change in calcium ion concentration.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This, in turn, releases nitric oxide at the contact point of astrocytes and intermediate-sized blood vessels, the arterioles.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Nitric oxide is a vasodilator causing arterioles to expand and draw in more blood.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A single voxel's response signal over time is called its timecourse.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Typically, the unwanted signal, called the noise, from the scanner, random brain activity and similar elements is as big as the signal itself.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To eliminate these, fMRI studies repeat a stimulus presentation multiple times.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Spatial resolution of an fMRI study refers to how well it discriminates between nearby locations.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It is measured by the size of voxels, as in MRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A voxel is a three-dimensional rectangular cuboid, whose dimensions are set by the slice thickness, the area of a slice, and the grid imposed on the slice by the scanning process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Full-brain studies use larger voxels, while those that focus on specific regions of interest typically use smaller sizes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Sizes range from 4 to 5 mm, or with laminar resolution fMRI (lfMRI), to submillimeter.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Smaller voxels contain fewer neurons on average, incorporate less blood flow, and hence have less signal than larger voxels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Smaller voxels imply longer scanning times, since scanning time directly rises with the number of voxels per slice and the number of slices.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This can lead both to discomfort for the subject inside the scanner and to loss of the magnetization signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A voxel typically contains a few million neurons and tens of billions of synapses, with the actual number depending on voxel size and the area of the brain being imaged.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The vascular arterial system supplying fresh blood branches into smaller and smaller vessels as it enters the brain surface and within-brain regions, culminating in a connected capillary bed within the brain.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The drainage system, similarly, merges into larger and larger veins as it carries away oxygen-depleted blood.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The dHb contribution to the fMRI signal is from both the capillaries near the area of activity and larger draining veins that may be farther away.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] For good spatial resolution, the signal from the large veins needs to be suppressed, since it does not correspond to the area where the neural activity is.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This can be achieved either by using strong static magnetic fields or by using spin-echo pulse sequences.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] With these, fMRI can examine a spatial range from millimeters to centimeters, and can hence identify Brodmann areas (centimeters), subcortical nuclei such as the caudate, putamen and thalamus, and hippocampal subfields such as the combined dentate gyrus/CA3, CA1, and subiculum.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Temporal resolution is the smallest time period of neural activity reliably separated out by fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One element deciding this is the sampling time, the TR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Below a TR of 1 or 2 seconds, however, scanning just generates sharper hemodynamic response (HR) curves, without adding much additional information (e.g. beyond what is alternatively achieved by mathematically interpolating the curve gaps at a lower TR).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Temporal resolution can be improved by staggering stimulus presentation across trials.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] If one-third of data trials are sampled normally, one-third at 1 s, 4 s, 7 s and so on, and the last third at 2 s, 5 s and 8 s, the combined data provide a resolution of 1 s, though with only one-third as many total events.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The time resolution needed depends on brain processing time for various events.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] An example of the broad range here is given by the visual processing system.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] What the eye sees is registered on the photoreceptors of the retina within a millisecond or so.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] These signals get to the primary visual cortex via the thalamus in tens of milliseconds.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Neuronal activity related to the act of seeing lasts for more than 100 ms.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A fast reaction, such as swerving to avoid a car crash, takes around 200 ms.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] By about half a second, awareness and reflection of the incident sets in.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Remembering a similar event may take a few seconds, and emotional or physiological changes such as fear arousal may last minutes or hours.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Learned changes, such as recognizing faces or scenes, may last days, months, or years.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Most fMRI experiments study brain processes lasting a few seconds, with the study conducted over some tens of minutes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Subjects may move their heads during that time, and this head motion needs to be corrected for.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] So does drift in the baseline signal over time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Boredom and learning may modify both subject behavior and cognitive processes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] When a person performs two tasks simultaneously or in overlapping fashion, the BOLD response is expected to add linearly.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is a fundamental assumption of many fMRI studies that is based on the principle that continuously differentiable systems can be expected to behave linearly when perturbations are small; they are linear to first order.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Linear addition means the only operation allowed on the individual responses before they are combined (added together) is a separate scaling of each.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since scaling is just multiplication by a constant number, this means an event that evokes, say, twice the neural response as another, can be modeled as the first event presented twice simultaneously.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The HR for the doubled-event is then just double that of the single event.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To the extent that the behavior is linear, the time course of the BOLD response to an arbitrary stimulus can be modeled by convolution of that stimulus with the impulse BOLD response.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Accurate time course modeling is important in estimating the BOLD response magnitude.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This strong assumption was first studied in 1996 by Boynton and colleagues, who checked the effects on the primary visual cortex of patterns flickering 8 times a second and presented for 3 to 24 seconds.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Their result showed that when visual contrast of the image was increased, the HR shape stayed the same but its amplitude increased proportionally.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] With some exceptions, responses to longer stimuli could also be inferred by adding together the responses for multiple shorter stimuli summing to the same longer duration.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In 1997, Dale and Buckner tested whether individual events, rather than blocks of some duration, also summed the same way, and found they did.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But they also found deviations from the linear model at time intervals less than 2 seconds.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A source of nonlinearity in the fMRI response is from the refractory period, where brain activity from a presented stimulus suppresses further activity on a subsequent, similar, stimulus.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] As stimuli become shorter, the refractory period becomes more noticeable.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The refractory period does not change with age, nor do the amplitudes of HRs.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The period differs across brain regions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In both the primary motor cortex and the visual cortex, the HR amplitude scales linearly with duration of a stimulus or response.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In the corresponding secondary regions, the supplementary motor cortex, which is involved in planning motor behavior, and the motion-sensitive V5 region, a strong refractory period is seen and the HR amplitude stays steady across a range of stimulus or response durations.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The refractory effect can be used in a way similar to habituation to see what features of a stimulus a person discriminates as new.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Further limits to linearity exist because of saturation: with large stimulation levels a maximum BOLD response is reached.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Researchers have checked the BOLD signal against both signals from implanted electrodes (mostly in monkeys) and signals of field potentials (that is the electric or magnetic field from the brain's activity, measured outside the skull) from EEG and MEG.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The local field potential, which includes both post-neuron-synaptic activity and internal neuron processing, better predicts the BOLD signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] So the BOLD contrast reflects mainly the inputs to a neuron and the neuron's integrative processing within its body, and less the output firing of neurons.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In humans, electrodes can be implanted only in patients who need surgery as treatment, but evidence suggests a similar relationship at least for the auditory cortex and the primary visual cortex.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Activation locations detected by BOLD fMRI in cortical areas (brain surface regions) are known to tally with CBF-based functional maps from PET scans.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Some regions just a few millimeters in size, such as the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) of the thalamus, which relays visual inputs from the retina to the visual cortex, have been shown to generate the BOLD signal correctly when presented with visual input.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Nearby regions such as the pulvinar nucleus were not stimulated for this task, indicating millimeter resolution for the spatial extent of the BOLD response, at least in thalamic nuclei.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In the rat brain, single-whisker touch has been shown to elicit BOLD signals from the somatosensory cortex.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] However, the BOLD signal cannot separate feedback and feedforward active networks in a region; the slowness of the vascular response means the final signal is the summed version of the whole region's network; blood flow is not discontinuous as the processing proceeds.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Also, both inhibitory and excitatory input to a neuron from other neurons sum and contribute to the BOLD signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Within a neuron these two inputs might cancel out.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The BOLD response can also be affected by a variety of factors, including disease, sedation, anxiety, medications that dilate blood vessels, and attention (neuromodulation).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The amplitude of the BOLD signal does not necessarily affect its shape.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A higher-amplitude signal may be seen for stronger neural activity, but peaking at the same place as a weaker signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Also, the amplitude does not necessarily reflect behavioral performance.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A complex cognitive task may initially trigger high-amplitude signals associated with good performance, but as the subject gets better at it, the amplitude may decrease with performance staying the same.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is expected to be due to increased efficiency in performing the task.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The BOLD response across brain regions cannot be compared directly even for the same task, since the density of neurons and the blood-supply characteristics are not constant across the brain.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] However, the BOLD response can often be compared across subjects for the same brain region and the same task.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] More recent characterization of the BOLD signal has used optogenetic techniques in rodents to precisely control neuronal firing while simultaneously monitoring the BOLD response using high field magnets (a technique sometimes referred to as "optofMRI").
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] These techniques suggest that neuronal firing is well correlated with the measured BOLD signal including approximately linear summation of the BOLD signal over closely spaced bursts of neuronal firing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Linear summation is an assumption of commonly used event-related fMRI designs.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Physicians use fMRI to assess how risky brain surgery or similar invasive treatment is for a patient and to learn how a normal, diseased or injured brain is functioning.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] They map the brain with fMRI to identify regions linked to critical functions such as speaking, moving, sensing, or planning.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is useful to plan for surgery and radiation therapy of the brain.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Clinical use of fMRI still lags behind research use.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Patients with brain pathologies are more difficult to scan with fMRI than are young healthy volunteers, the typical research-subject population.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Tumors and lesions can change the blood flow in ways not related to neural activity, masking the neural HR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Drugs such as antihistamines and even caffeine can affect HR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Some patients may have disorders such as compulsive lying, which makes certain studies impossible.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It is harder for those with clinical problems to stay still for long.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Using head restraints or bite bars may injure epileptics who have a seizure inside the scanner; bite bars may also discomfort those with dental prostheses.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Mapping of functional areas and understanding lateralization of language and memory help surgeons avoid removing critical brain regions when they have to operate and remove brain tissue.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is of particular importance in removing tumors and in patients who have intractable temporal lobe epilepsy.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Lesioning tumors requires pre-surgical planning to ensure no functionally useful tissue is removed needlessly.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Recovered depressed patients have shown altered fMRI activity in the cerebellum, and this may indicate a tendency to relapse.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Pharmacological fMRI, assaying brain activity after drugs are administered, can be used to check how much a drug penetrates the blood–brain barrier and dose vs effect information of the medication.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Research is primarily performed in non-human primates such as the rhesus macaque.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] These studies can be used both to check or predict human results and to validate the fMRI technique itself.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But the studies are difficult because it is hard to motivate an animal to stay still and typical inducements such as juice trigger head movement while the animal swallows it.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It is also expensive to maintain a colony of larger animals such as the macaque.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The goal of fMRI data analysis is to detect correlations between brain activation and a task the subject performs during the scan.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It also aims to discover correlations with the specific cognitive states, such as memory and recognition, induced in the subject.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The BOLD signature of activation is relatively weak, however, so other sources of noise in the acquired data must be carefully controlled.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This means that a series of processing steps must be performed on the acquired images before the actual statistical search for task-related activation can begin.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Nevertheless, it is possible to predict, for example, the emotions a person is experiencing solely from their fMRI, with a high degree of accuracy.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Noise is unwanted changes to the MR signal from elements not of interest to the study.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The five main sources of noise in fMRI are thermal noise, system noise, physiological noise, random neural activity and differences in both mental strategies and behavior across people and across tasks within a person.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Thermal noise multiplies in line with the static field strength, but physiological noise multiplies as the square of the field strength.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since the signal also multiplies as the square of the field strength, and since physiological noise is a large proportion of total noise, higher field strengths above 3 T do not always produce proportionately better images.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Heat causes electrons to move around and distort the current in the fMRI detector, producing thermal noise.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Thermal noise rises with the temperature.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It also depends on the range of frequencies detected by the receiver coil and its electrical resistance.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It affects all voxels similarly, independent of anatomy.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] System noise is from the imaging hardware.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One form is scanner drift, caused by the superconducting magnet's field drifting over time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Another form is changes in the current or voltage distribution of the brain itself inducing changes in the receiver coil and reducing its sensitivity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A procedure called impedance matching is used to bypass this inductance effect.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] There could also be noise from the magnetic field not being uniform.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is often adjusted for by using shimming coils, small magnets physically inserted, say into the subject's mouth, to patch the magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The nonuniformities are often near brain sinuses such as the ear and plugging the cavity for long periods can be discomfiting.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The scanning process acquires the MR signal in k-space, in which overlapping spatial frequencies (that is repeated edges in the sample's volume) are each represented with lines.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Transforming this into voxels introduces some loss and distortions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Physiological noise is from head and brain movement in the scanner from breathing, heart beats, or the subject fidgeting, tensing, or making physical responses such as button presses.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Head movements cause the voxel-to-neurons mapping to change while scanning is in progress.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Noise due to head movement is a particular issue when working with children, although there are measures that can be taken to reduce head motion when scanning children, such as changes in experimental design and training prior to the scanning session.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since fMRI is acquired in slices, after movement, a voxel continues to refer to the same absolute location in space while the neurons underneath it would have changed.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Another source of physiological noise is the change in the rate of blood flow, blood volume, and use of oxygen over time.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This last component contributes to two-thirds of physiological noise, which, in turn, is the main contributor to total noise.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Even with the best experimental design, it is not possible to control and constrain all other background stimuli impinging on a subject—scanner noise, random thoughts, physical sensations, and the like.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] These produce neural activity independent of the experimental manipulation.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] These are not amenable to mathematical modeling and have to be controlled by the study design.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A person's strategies to respond or react to a stimulus, and to solve problems, often change over time and over tasks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This generates variations in neural activity from trial to trial within a subject.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Across people too neural activity differs for similar reasons.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Researchers often conduct pilot studies to see how participants typically perform for the task under consideration.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] They also often train subjects how to respond or react in a trial training session prior to the scanning one.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The scanner platform generates a 3 D volume of the subject's head every TR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This consists of an array of voxel intensity values, one value per voxel in the scan.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The voxels are arranged one after the other, unfolding the three-dimensional structure into a single line.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Several such volumes from a session are joined to form a 4 D volume corresponding to a run, for the time period the subject stayed in the scanner without adjusting head position.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This 4 D volume is the starting point for analysis.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The first part of that analysis is preprocessing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The first step in preprocessing is conventionally slice timing correction.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The MR scanner acquires different slices within a single brain volume at different times, and hence the slices represent brain activity at different timepoints.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since this complicates later analysis, a timing correction is applied to bring all slices to the same timepoint reference.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is done by assuming the timecourse of a voxel is smooth when plotted as a dotted line.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Hence the voxel's intensity value at other times not in the sampled frames can be calculated by filling in the dots to create a continuous curve.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Head motion correction is another common preprocessing step.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] When the head moves, the neurons under a voxel move and hence its timecourse now represents largely that of some other voxel in the past.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Hence the timecourse curve is effectively cut and pasted from one voxel to another.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Motion correction tries different ways of undoing this to see which undoing of the cut-and-paste produces the smoothest timecourse for all voxels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The undoing is by applying a rigid-body transform to the volume, by shifting and rotating the whole volume data to account for motion.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The transformed volume is compared statistically to the volume at the first timepoint to see how well they match, using a cost function such as correlation or mutual information.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The transformation that gives the minimal cost function is chosen as the model for head motion.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Since the head can move in a vastly varied number of ways, it is not possible to search for all possible candidates; nor is there right now an algorithm that provides a globally optimal solution independent of the first transformations we try in a chain.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Distortion corrections account for field nonuniformities of the scanner.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One method, as described before, is to use shimming coils.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Another is to recreate a field map of the main field by acquiring two images with differing echo times.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] If the field were uniform, the differences between the two images also would be uniform.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Note these are not true preprocessing techniques since they are independent of the study itself.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Bias field estimation is a real preprocessing technique using mathematical models of the noise from distortion, such as Markov random fields and expectation maximization algorithms, to correct for distortion.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In general, fMRI studies acquire both many functional images with fMRI and a structural image with MRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The structural image is usually of a higher resolution and depends on a different signal, the T1 magnetic field decay after excitation.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To demarcate regions of interest in the functional image, one needs to align it with the structural one.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Even when whole-brain analysis is done, to interpret the final results, that is to figure out which regions the active voxels fall in, one has to align the functional image to the structural one.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This is done with a coregistration algorithm that works similar to the motion-correction one, except that here the resolutions are different, and the intensity values cannot be directly compared since the generating signal is different.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Typical MRI studies scan a few different subjects.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] To integrate the results across subjects, one possibility is to use a common brain atlas, and adjust all the brains to align to the atlas, and then analyze them as a single group.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The atlases commonly used are the Talairach one, a single brain of an elderly woman created by Jean Talairach, and the Montreal Neurological Institute (MNI) one.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The second is a probabilistic map created by combining scans from over a hundred individuals.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This normalization to a standard template is done by mathematically checking which combination of stretching, squeezing, and warping reduces the differences between the target and the reference.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] While this is conceptually similar to motion correction, the changes required are more complex than just translation and rotation, and hence optimization even more likely to depend on the first transformations in the chain that is checked.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Temporal filtering is the removal of frequencies of no interest from the signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A voxel's intensity change over time can be represented as the sum of a number of different repeating waves with differing periods and heights.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A plot with these periods on the x-axis and the heights on the y-axis is called a power spectrum, and this plot is created with the Fourier transform technique.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Temporal filtering amounts to removing the periodic waves not of interest to us from the power spectrum, and then summing the waves back again, using the inverse Fourier transform to create a new timecourse for the voxel.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A high-pass filter removes the lower frequencies, and the lowest frequency that can be identified with this technique is the reciprocal of twice the TR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A low-pass filter removes the higher frequencies, while a band-pass filter removes all frequencies except the particular range of interest.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Smoothing, or spatial filtering, is the idea of averaging the intensities of nearby voxels to produce a smooth spatial map of intensity change across the brain or region of interest.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The averaging is often done by convolution with a Gaussian filter, which, at every spatial point, weights neighboring voxels by their distance, with the weights falling exponentially following the bell curve.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] If the true spatial extent of activation, that is the spread of the cluster of voxels simultaneously active, matches the width of the filter used, this process improves the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It also makes the total noise for each voxel follow a bell-curve distribution, since adding together a large number of independent, identical distributions of any kind produces the bell curve as the limit case.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But if the presumed spatial extent of activation does not match the filter, signal is reduced.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One common approach to analysing fMRI data is to consider each voxel separately within the framework of the general linear model.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The model assumes, at every time point, that the hemodynamic response (HR) is equal to the scaled and summed version of the events active at that point.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A researcher creates a design matrix specifying which events are active at any timepoint.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One common way is to create a matrix with one column per overlapping event, and one row per time point, and to mark it if a particular event, say a stimulus, is active at that time point.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] One then assumes a specific shape for the HR, leaving only its amplitude changeable in active voxels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The design matrix and this shape are used to generate a prediction of the exact HR of the voxel at every timepoint, using the mathematical procedure of convolution.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This prediction does not include the scaling required for every event before summing them.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The basic model assumes the observed HR is the predicted HR scaled by the weights for each event and then added, with noise mixed in.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This generates a set of linear equations with more equations than unknowns.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] A linear equation has an exact solution, under most conditions, when equations and unknowns match.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Hence one could choose any subset of the equations, with the number equal to the number of variables, and solve them.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But, when these solutions are plugged into the left-out equations, there will be a mismatch between the right and left sides, the error.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The GLM model attempts to find the scaling weights that minimize the sum of the squares of the error.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This method is provably optimal if the error were distributed as a bell curve, and if the scaling-and-summing model were accurate.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] For a more mathematical description of the GLM model, see generalized linear models.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The GLM model does not take into account the contribution of relationships between multiple voxels.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Whereas GLM analysis methods assess whether a voxel or region's signal amplitude is higher or lower for one condition than another, newer statistical models such as multi-voxel pattern analysis (MVPA), utilize the unique contributions of multiple voxels within a voxel-population.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] In a typical implementation, a classifier or more basic algorithm is trained to distinguish trials for different conditions within a subset of the data.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The trained model is then tested by predicting the conditions of the remaining (independent) data.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] This approach is most typically achieved by training and testing on different scanner sessions or runs.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] If the classifier is linear, then the training model is a set of weights used to scale the value in each voxel before summing them to generate a single number that determines the condition for each testing set trial.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] More information on training and testing classifiers is at statistical classification.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] MVPA allows for inferences about the information content of the underlying neural representations reflected in the BOLD signal, though there is a controversy about whether information detected by this method reflects information encoded at the level of columns, or higher spatial scales.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Moreover, its harder to decode information from the prefrontal cortex compared to visual cortex and such differences in sensitivity across regions makes comparisons across regions problematic.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It is common to combine fMRI signal acquisition with tracking of participants' responses and reaction times.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Physiological measures such as heart rate, breathing, skin conductance (rate of sweating), and eye movements are sometimes captured simultaneously with fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The method can also be combined with other brain-imaging techniques such as transcranial stimulation, direct cortical stimulation and, especially, EEG.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The fMRI procedure can also be combined with near-infrared spectroscopy (NIRS) to have supplementary information about both oxyhemoglobin and deoxyhemoglobin.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The fMRI technique can complement or supplement other techniques because of its unique strengths and gaps.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It can noninvasively record brain signals without risks of ionising radiation inherent in other scanning methods, such as CT or PET scans.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It can also record signal from all regions of the brain, unlike EEG/MEG, which are biased toward the cortical surface.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But fMRI temporal resolution is poorer than that of EEG since the HR takes tens of seconds to climb to its peak.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Combining EEG with fMRI is hence potentially powerful because the two have complementary strengths—EEG has high temporal resolution, and fMRI high spatial resolution.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] But simultaneous acquisition needs to account for the EEG signal from varying blood flow triggered by the fMRI gradient field, and the EEG signal from the static field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] While fMRI stands out due to its potential to capture neural processes associated with health and disease, brain stimulation techniques such as transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) have the power to alter these neural processes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Therefore, a combination of both is needed to investigate the mechanisms of action of TMS treatment and on the other hand introduce causality into otherwise pure correlational observations.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] The current state-of-the-art setup for these concurrent TMS/fMRI experiments comprises a large-volume head coil, usually a birdcage coil, with the MR-compatible TMS coil being mounted inside that birdcage coil.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] It was applied in a multitude of experiments studying local and network interactions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] However, classic setups with the TMS coil placed inside MR birdcage-type head coil are characterised by poor signal to noise ratios compared to multi-channel receive arrays used in clinical neuroimaging today.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] Moreover, the presence of the TMS coil inside the MR birdcage coil causes artefacts beneath the TMS coil, i.e. at the stimulation target.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p01] For these reasons new MR coil arrays were currently developed dedicated to concurrent TMS/fMRI experiments.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] If the baseline condition is too close to maximum activation, certain processes may not be represented appropriately.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Another limitation on experimental design is head motion, which can lead to artificial intensity changes of the fMRI signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In a block design, two or more conditions are alternated by blocks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Each block will have a duration of a certain number of fMRI scans and within each block only one condition is presented.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] By making the conditions differ in only the cognitive process of interest, the fMRI signal that differentiates the conditions should represent this cognitive process of interest.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This is known as the subtraction paradigm.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The increase in fMRI signal in response to a stimulus is additive.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This means that the amplitude of the hemodynamic response (HR) increases when multiple stimuli are presented in rapid succession.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] When each block is alternated with a rest condition in which the HR has enough time to return to baseline, a maximum amount of variability is introduced in the signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] As such, we conclude that block designs offer considerable statistical power.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] There are however severe drawbacks to this method, as the signal is very sensitive to signal drift, such as head motion, especially when only a few blocks are used.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Another limiting factor is a poor choice of baseline, as it may prevent meaningful conclusions from being drawn.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] There are also problems with many tasks lacking the ability to be repeated.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Since within each block only one condition is presented, randomization of stimulus types is not possible within a block.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This makes the type of stimulus within each block very predictable.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] As a consequence, participants may become aware of the order of the events.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Event-related designs allow more real world testing, however, the statistical power of event related designs is inherently low, because the signal change in the BOLD fMRI signal following a single stimulus presentation is small.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Both block and event-related designs are based on the subtraction paradigm, which assumes that specific cognitive processes can be added selectively in different conditions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Any difference in blood flow (the BOLD signal) between these two conditions is then assumed to reflect the differing cognitive process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In addition, this model assumes that a cognitive process can be selectively added to a set of active cognitive processes without affecting them.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Overlapping signals in fMRI are a significant challenge in cognitive neuroscience research, particularly when multiple stimuli or tasks are presented in close temporal proximity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The BOLD response has a slow temporal resolution compared to the rapid succession of cognitive events.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This causes signals from different brain processes to overlap, making it difficult to differentiate which neural activity is associated with specific stimuli or tasks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This overlap reduces the precision of event-related fMRI analyses, complicating interpretations of brain function.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Traditional fMRI designs, such as block or event-related designs, face limitations in managing this signal overlap, especially in studies with non-randomized, alternating designs, where the same tasks or stimuli may appear repeatedly and close together.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] As a result, the timing of stimuli becomes a crucial factor in ensuring that the fMRI signal from one event is sufficiently distinct from the next.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] To address these challenges, researchers employ techniques like deconvolution, which mathematically separates the overlapping BOLD responses.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In 2023, Das and colleagues demonstrated various ways on optimizing timing between individual events such that convolution of signals evoked by them that are close to each other can be minimized.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These methods attempt to estimate the contribution of each neural event to the overall signal, allowing for more accurate interpretation of brain activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Advances in analytical methods, such as specialized tools for optimizing experimental designs, are crucial for mitigating the effects of signal overlap and improving the reliability of fMRI studies.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It never stops functioning and firing neuronal signals, as well as using oxygen as long as the person in question is alive.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In fact, in Stark and Squire's, 2001 study *When zero is not zero: The problem of ambiguous baseline conditions in fMRI*, activity in the medial temporal lobe (as well as in other brain regions) was substantially higher during rest than during several alternative baseline conditions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The effect of this elevated activity during rest was to reduce, eliminate, or even reverse the sign of the activity during task conditions relevant to memory functions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These results demonstrate that periods of rest are associated with significant cognitive activity and are therefore not an optimal baseline for cognition tasks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In order to discern baseline and activation conditions it is necessary to interpret a lot of information.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This includes situations as simple as breathing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Periodic blocks may result in identical data of other variance in the data if the person breathes at a regular rate of 1 breath/5sec, and the blocks occur every 10s, thus impairing the data.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Neuroimaging methods such as fMRI and MRI offer a measure of the activation of certain brain areas in response to cognitive tasks engaged in during the scanning process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Data obtained during this time allow cognitive neuroscientists to gain information regarding the role of particular brain regions in cognitive function.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, an issue arises when certain brain regions are alleged by researchers to identify the activation of previously labeled cognitive processes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] (1) In the present study, when task comparison A was presented, brain area Z was active.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] (2) In other studies, when cognitive process X was putatively engaged, then brain area Z was active.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] (3) Thus, the activity of area Z in the present study demonstrates engagement of cognitive process X by task comparison A.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This is a 'reverse inference', in that it reasons backwards from the presence of brain activation to the engagement of a particular cognitive function.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Reverse inference demonstrates the logical fallacy of affirming what you just found, although this logic could be supported by instances where a certain outcome is generated solely by a specific occurrence.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] With regard to the brain and brain function it is seldom that a particular brain region is activated solely by one cognitive process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Some suggestions to improve the legitimacy of reverse inference have included both increasing the selectivity of response in the brain region of interest and increasing the prior probability of the cognitive process in question.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, Poldrack suggests that reverse inference should be used merely as a guide to direct further inquiry rather than a direct means to interpret results.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Forward inference is a data driven method that uses patterns of brain activation to distinguish between competing cognitive theories.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It shares characteristics with cognitive psychology's dissociation logic and philosophy's forward chaining.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] For example, Henson discusses forward inference's contribution to the "single process theory vs. dual process theory" debate with regard to recognition memory.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Forward inference supports the dual process theory by demonstrating that there are two qualitatively different brain activation patterns when distinguishing between "remember vs. know judgments".
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The main issue with forward inference is that it is a correlational method.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Therefore, one cannot be completely confident that brain regions activated during cognitive process are completely necessary for that execution of those processes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In fact, there are many known cases that demonstrate just that.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] For example, the hippocampus has been shown to be activated during classical conditioning, however lesion studies have demonstrated that classical conditioning can occur without the hippocampus.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The most common risk to participants in an fMRI study is claustrophobia and there are reported risks for pregnant women to go through the scanning process.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Scanning sessions also subject participants to loud high-pitched noises from Lorentz forces induced in the gradient coils by the rapidly switching current in the powerful static field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The gradient switching can also induce currents in the body causing nerve tingling.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Implanted medical devices such as pacemakers could malfunction because of these currents.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The radio-frequency field of the excitation coil may heat up the body, and this has to be monitored more carefully in those running a fever, the diabetic, and those with circulatory problems.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Local burning from metal necklaces and other jewellery is also a risk.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The strong static magnetic field can cause damage by pulling in nearby heavy metal objects converting them to projectiles.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] There is no proven risk of biological harm from even very powerful static magnetic fields.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, genotoxic (i.e., potentially carcinogenic) effects of MRI scanning have been demonstrated in vivo and in vitro, leading a recent review to recommend "a need for further studies and prudent use in order to avoid unnecessary examinations, according to the precautionary principle".
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The first fMRI studies validated the technique against brain activity known, from other techniques, to be correlated to tasks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] By the early 2000s, fMRI studies began to discover novel correlations.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Still their technical disadvantages have spurred researchers to try more advanced ways to increase the power of both clinical and research studies.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] MRI, in general, has better spatial resolution than EEG and MEG, but not as good a resolution as invasive procedures such as single-unit electrodes.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] While typical resolutions are in the millimeter range, ultra-high-resolution MRI or MR spectroscopy works at a resolution of tens of micrometers.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It uses 7 T fields, small-bore scanners that can fit small animals such as rats, and external contrast agents such as fine iron oxide.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Fitting a human requires larger-bore scanners, which make higher fields strengths harder to achieve, especially if the field has to be uniform; it also requires either internal contrast such as BOLD or a non-toxic external contrast agent unlike iron oxide.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Parallel imaging is another technique to improve spatial resolution.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This uses multiple coils for excitation and reception.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Spatial resolution improves as the square root of the number of coils used.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This can be done either with a phased array where the coils are combined in parallel and often sample overlapping areas with gaps in the sampling or with massive coil arrays, which are a much denser set of receivers separate from the excitation coils.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These, however, pick up signals better from the brain surface, and less well from deeper structures such as the hippocampus.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Temporal resolution of fMRI is limited by: (1) the feedback mechanism that raises the blood flow operating slowly; (2) having to wait until net magnetization recovers before sampling a slice again; and (3) having to acquire multiple slices to cover the whole brain or region of interest.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Advanced techniques to improve temporal resolution address these issues.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Using multiple coils speeds up acquisition time in exact proportion to the coils used.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Another technique is to decide which parts of the signal matter less and drop those.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This could be either those sections of the image that repeat often in a spatial map (that is small clusters dotting the image periodically) or those sections repeating infrequently (larger clusters).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The first, a high-pass filter in k-space, has been proposed by Gary H.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These mechanisms assume the researcher has an idea of the expected shape of the activation image.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Typical gradient-echo EPI uses two gradient coils within a slice, and turns on first one coil and then the other, tracing a set of lines in k-space.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Turning on both gradient coils can generate angled lines, which cover the same grid space faster.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Both gradient coils can also be turned on in a specific sequence to trace a spiral shape in k-space.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This spiral imaging sequence acquires images faster than gradient-echo sequences, but needs more math transformations (and consequent assumptions) since converting back to voxel space requires the data be in grid form (a set of equally spaced points in both horizontal and vertical directions).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] BOLD contrast depends on blood flow, which is both sluggish in response to stimulus and subject to noisy influences.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Other biomarkers now looked at to provide better contrast include temperature, acidity/alkalinity (pH), calcium-sensitive agents, neuronal magnetic field, and the Lorentz effect.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Temperature contrast depends on changes in brain temperature from its activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The initial burning of glucose raises the temperature, and the subsequent inflow of fresh, cold blood lowers it.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These changes alter the magnetic properties of tissue.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Since the internal contrast is too difficult to measure, external agents such as thulium compounds are used to enhance the effect.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Contrast based on pH depends on changes in the acid/alkaline balance of brain cells when they go active.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Calcium-sensitive agents make MRI more sensitive to calcium concentrations, with calcium ions often being the messengers for cellular signalling pathways in active neurons.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Neuronal magnetic field contrast measures the magnetic and electric changes from neuronal firing directly.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Lorentz-effect imaging tries to measure the physical displacement of active neurons carrying an electric current within the strong static field.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Vascular-space occupancy (VASO) measures changes in cerebral blood volume (CBV), which is a less ambiguous marker of neural activity than BOLD.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The signal intensity is inversely proportional to CBV, with typical signal changes around -1.5%.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It relies on the T₁ difference between blood and the surrounding tissue.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Because it nulls the blood signal, VASO eliminates the large veins contribution to the MR signal, reducing the risk of falsely localizing brain activity to nearby draining veins, and achieving high spatial specificity, which makes the technique well-suited for layer-specific fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] VASO allows for the reliable quantification of physiological parameters such as the cerebral metabolic rate of oxygen or the oxygen extraction fraction.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, the approach suffers from some limitations compared to techniques that rely on the BOLD signal.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] VASO generally has lower sensitivity, lower SNR and lower CNR, as well as reduced imaging efficiency and higher susceptibility to motion artifacts.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Balanced Steady-State Free Precession (bSSFP) fMRI: bSSFP offers high SNR efficiency due to optimized magnetization usage, leading to high tSNR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It also features reduced distortion because of its short readouts, minimizing susceptibility-induced distortion and signal dropout compared to GRE-EPI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It's compatible with advanced short-readout strategies like multi-shot, spiral, and radial trajectories.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, bSSFP is prone to banding artifacts from off-resonance effects and has a complex contrast mechanism influenced by T₂/T₁, diffusion, and off-resonance.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It also tends to have a higher SAR compared to GRE sequences.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Pass-Band bSSFP: This variant has a flat magnitude response over a broad frequency range (approximately 75% of 1/TR).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Its contrast is T₂-based, driven by diffusion in susceptibility gradients and intravascular T₂ changes, with low sensitivity to frequency shifts.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] While offering lower contrast than long-TE GRE, it provides superior robustness to off-resonance and shim variations, making efficient whole-brain coverage achievable with minimal phase cycling.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Larger Flip angles could be used to operate in Passband region.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Transition-Band bSSFP: This type operates within a narrow frequency range (around 10–15% of 1/TR) with a steep magnitude and phase response.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Its BOLD sensitivity is frequency-driven, where small frequency shifts cause large signal changes, potentially yielding high functional contrast (10–40%).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, this makes it highly dependent on the baseline resonance frequency of the voxel and critical of shimming quality, challenging whole-brain coverage without multiple acquisitions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Applications: bSSFP techniques can be beneficial for layer-specific imaging or studies requiring high SNR and excellent temporal resolution, especially in low-field or low-SNR brain regions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Multi-echo, Multi-contrast (SAGE) fMRI: SAGE techniques aim to combine the high sensitivity of multi-gradient echo (MGE) with the microvascular specificity of spin-echo (SE).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] They simultaneously acquire multiple gradient-echoes and spin-echoes (e.g., 2 GRE, 2 Asymmetric SE, 1 SE), allowing for optimized Contrast-to-Noise Ratio (CNR) and temporal Signal-to-Noise Ratio (tSNR) across varying T₂* values.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Echoes can be weighted to emphasize either T₂*-BOLD contrast (wT₂*), similar to GRE, or T₂-BOLD contrast (wT₂), similar to SE.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] For instance, wT₂* weighting uses pre-refocusing GREs and Asymmetric Spin Echoes (ASEs), while wT₂ weighting uses post-refocusing ASEs and the pure SE.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This method is particularly useful for studies focused on vascular physiology or when needing to avoid interscan variability.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] A limitation is its reliance on acceleration methods like multiband (MB) or SENSE.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Silent fMRI: Based on 3D radial Rotating Ultra-Fast Imaging Sequence (RUFIS), Looping Star enhances RUFIS/Zero Echo Time (ZTE) by adding time-multiplexed gradient refocusing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This enables multi-echo acquisition beyond the initial FID (TE ≈ 0) to provide essential T₂* BOLD contrast.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Its primary advantage is significantly reduced acoustic noise, approximately 25 dBA quieter than conventional GRE-EPI (a ~98% reduction).
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Limitations include potential echo mixing artifacts requiring correction and possibly reduced tSNR and BOLD sensitivity compared to GRE-EPI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Studies have shown that while looping star identifies similar activation networks to GE-EPI, it may exhibit reduced activation extent and lower T-values due to lower tSNR.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Its BOLD sensitivity was found to be around 69.5% relative to GE-EPI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Applications: Silent fMRI techniques are particularly valuable for auditory tasks (to avoid stimulus-correlated scanner noise), pediatric studies, or examining subjects sensitive to loud noise.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Some experiments have shown the neural correlates of peoples' brand preferences.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] McClure used fMRI to show the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, hippocampus and midbrain were more active when people knowingly drank Coca-Cola as opposed to when they drank unlabeled Coke.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Other studies have shown the brain activity that characterizes men's preference for sports cars, and even differences between Democrats and Republicans in their reaction to campaign commercials with images of the 9/11 attacks.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Neuromarketing companies have seized on these studies as a better tool to poll user preferences than the conventional survey technique.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] One such company was BrightHouse, now shut down.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Another is Oxford, UK-based Neurosense, which advises clients how they could potentially use fMRI as part of their marketing business activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] At least two companies have been set up to use fMRI in lie detection: No Lie MRI and the Cephos Corporation.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] No Lie MRI charges close to $5000 for its services.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] These companies depend on evidence such as that from a study by Joshua Greene at Harvard University suggesting the prefrontal cortex is more active in those contemplating lying.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] However, there is still a fair amount of controversy over whether these techniques are reliable enough to be used in a legal setting.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Some studies indicate that while there is an overall positive correlation, there is a great deal of variation between findings and in some cases considerable difficulty in replicating the findings.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] A federal magistrate judge in Tennessee prohibited fMRI evidence to back up a defendant's claim of telling the truth, on the grounds that such scans do not measure up to the legal standard of scientific evidence..
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Most researchers agree that the ability of fMRI to detect deception in a real life setting has not been established.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Use of the fMRI has been left out of legal debates throughout its history.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Use of this technology has not been allowed due to holes in the evidence supporting fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] First, most evidence supporting fMRIs accuracy was done in a lab under controlled circumstances with solid facts.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This type of testing does not pertain to real life.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Real-life scenarios can be much more complicated with many other affecting factors.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] It has been shown that many other factors affect BOLD other than a typical lie.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] There have been tests done showing that drug use alters blood flow in the brain, which drastically affects the outcome of BOLD testing.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Furthermore, individuals with diseases or disorders such as schizophrenia or compulsive lying can lead to abnormal results as well.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Lastly, there is an ethical question relating to fMRI scanning.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] This testing of BOLD has led to controversy over if fMRIs are an invasion of privacy.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Being able to scan and interpret what people are thinking may be thought of as immoral and the controversy still continues.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Because of these factors and more, fMRI evidence has been excluded from any form of legal system.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The testing is too uncontrolled and unpredictable.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Therefore, it has been stated that fMRI has much more testing to do before it can be considered viable in the eyes of the legal system.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Some scholars have criticized fMRI studies for problematic statistical analyses, often based on low-power, small-sample studies.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Other fMRI researchers have defended their work as valid.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In 2018, Turner and colleagues have suggested that the small sizes affect the replicability of task-based fMRI studies and claimed that even datasets with at least 100 participants the results may not be well replicated, although there are debates on it.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In one real but satirical fMRI study, a dead salmon was shown pictures of humans in different emotional states.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The authors provided evidence, according to two different commonly used statistical tests, of areas in the salmon's brain suggesting meaningful activity.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The study was used to highlight the need for more careful statistical analyses in fMRI research, given the large number of voxels in a typical fMRI scan and the multiple comparisons problem.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Before the controversies were publicized in 2010, between 25 and 40% of studies on fMRI being published were not using the corrected comparisons.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] But by 2012, that number had dropped to 10%.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Sally Satel, writing in Time, cautioned that while brain scans have scientific value, individual brain areas often serve multiple purposes and "reverse inferences" as commonly used in press reports carry a significant chance of drawing invalid conclusions.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In 2015, it was discovered that a statistical bug was found in the fMRI computations which likely invalidated at least 40,000 fMRI studies preceding 2015, and researchers suggest that results prior to the bug fix cannot be relied upon.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] Furthermore, it was later shown that how one sets the parameters in the software determines the false positive rate.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In other words, study outcome can be determined by changing software parameters.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In 2020 professor Ahmad Hariri, (Duke University) one of the first researchers to use fMRI, performed a largescale experiment that sought to test the reliability of fMRI on individual people.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] In the study, he copied protocols from 56 published papers in psychology that used fMRI.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] The results suggest that fMRI has poor reliability when it comes to individual cases, but good reliability when it comes to general human thought patterns.
[src:mri-physics/functional-magnetic-resonance-imaging-p02] A 2025 study published in *Nature Neuroscience* found that BOLD signals in fMRI did not consistently relate to changes in neuronal activity.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] In physics, **Larmor precession** (named after Joseph Larmor) is the precession of the magnetic moment of an object about an external magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The phenomenon is conceptually similar to the precession of a tilted classical gyroscope in an external torque-exerting gravitational field.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] Objects with a magnetic moment also have angular momentum and effective internal electric current proportional to their angular momentum; these include electrons, protons, other fermions, many atomic and nuclear systems, as well as classical macroscopic systems.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency, B is the magnitude of the applied magnetic field, and $\gamma$ is the gyromagnetic ratio for a particle of charge $-e$ , equal to $-{\frac {eg}{2m}}$ , where m is the mass of the precessing system, while g is the *g*-factor of the system.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The *g*-factor is the unit-less proportionality factor relating the system's angular momentum to the intrinsic magnetic moment; in classical physics it is 1 for any rigid object in which the charge and mass density are identically distributed.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The Larmor frequency is independent of the angle between ${\vec {J}}$ and ${\vec {B}}$ .
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] In nuclear physics the *g*-factor of a given system includes the effect of the nucleon spins, their orbital angular momenta, and their couplings.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] Generally, the *g*-factors are very difficult to calculate for such many-body systems, but they have been measured to high precision for most nuclei.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The Larmor frequency is important in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The gyromagnetic ratios, which give the Larmor frequencies at a given magnetic field strength, have been measured and tabulated.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] Crucially, the Larmor frequency is independent of the polar angle between the applied magnetic field and the magnetic moment direction.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] This is what makes it a key concept in fields such as nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR), since the precession rate does not depend on the spatial orientation of the spins.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The above equation is the one that is used in most applications.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] where $\gamma$ is the relativistic Lorentz factor (not to be confused with the gyromagnetic ratio above).
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] one can rewrite the first term on the right side of the BMT equation as $(-u^{\tau }w^{\lambda }+u^{\lambda }w^{\tau })a_{\lambda }$ , where $w^{\tau }=du^{\tau }/ds$ is four-acceleration.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] This term describes Fermi–Walker transport and leads to Thomas precession.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The second term is associated with Larmor precession.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The Beam-Optical version of the Thomas-BMT, from the *Quantum Theory of Charged-Particle Beam Optics*, applicable in accelerator optics.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] A 1935 paper published by Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz predicted the existence of ferromagnetic resonance of the Larmor precession, which was independently verified in experiments by J.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] Larmor precession is important in nuclear magnetic resonance, magnetic resonance imaging, electron paramagnetic resonance, muon spin resonance, and neutron spin echo.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] It is also important for the alignment of cosmic dust grains, which is a cause of the polarization of starlight.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] To calculate the spin of a particle in a magnetic field, one must in general also take into account Thomas precession if the particle is moving.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] The spin angular momentum of an electron precesses counter-clockwise about the direction of the magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/larmor-precession] An electron has a negative charge, so the direction of its magnetic moment is opposite to that of its spin.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI is widely used in hospitals and clinics for medical diagnosis, staging and follow-up of disease.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Compared to CT, MRI provides better contrast in images of soft tissues, e.g. in the brain or abdomen.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, it may be perceived as less comfortable by patients, due to the usually longer and louder measurements with the subject in a long, confining tube, although "open" MRI designs mostly relieve this.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Additionally, implants and other non-removable metal in the body can pose a risk and may exclude some patients from undergoing an MRI examination safely.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI was originally called NMRI (nuclear magnetic resonance imaging), but "nuclear" was dropped to avoid negative associations.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Certain atomic nuclei are able to absorb radio frequency (RF) energy when placed in an external magnetic field; the resultant evolving spin polarization can induce an RF signal in a radio frequency coil and thereby be detected.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In other words, the nuclear magnetic spin of protons in the hydrogen nuclei resonates with the RF incident waves and emit coherent radiation with compact direction, energy (frequency) and phase.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This coherent amplified radiation is then detected by RF antennas close to the subject being examined.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In clinical and research MRI, hydrogen atoms are most often used to generate a macroscopic polarized radiation that is detected by the antennas.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Hydrogen atoms are naturally abundant in humans and other biological organisms, particularly in water and fat.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] For this reason, most MRI scans essentially map the location of water and fat in the body.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Pulses of radio waves excite the nuclear spin energy transition, and magnetic field gradients localize the polarization in space.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] By varying the parameters of the pulse sequence, different contrasts may be generated between tissues based on the relaxation properties of the hydrogen atoms therein.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since its development in the 1970s and 1980s, MRI has proven to be a versatile imaging technique.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] While MRI is most prominently used in diagnostic medicine and biomedical research, it also may be used to form images of non-living objects, such as mummies.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Diffusion MRI and functional MRI extend the utility of MRI to capture neuronal tracts and blood flow respectively in the nervous system, in addition to detailed spatial images.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The sustained increase in demand for MRI within health systems has led to concerns about cost effectiveness and overdiagnosis.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The whole system is controlled by one or more computers.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In most medical applications, hydrogen nuclei, which consist solely of a proton, that are in tissues create a signal that is processed to form an image of the body in terms of the density of those nuclei in a specific region.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Given that the protons are affected by fields from other atoms to which they are bonded, it is possible to separate responses from hydrogen in specific compounds.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To perform a study, the person is positioned within an MRI scanner that forms a strong magnetic field around the area to be imaged.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] First, energy from an oscillating magnetic field is temporarily applied to the patient at the appropriate resonance frequency.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Scanning with X and Y gradient coils causes a selected region of the patient to experience the exact magnetic field required for the energy to be absorbed.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The atoms are excited by a RF pulse and the resultant signal is measured by one or more receiving coils.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The RF signal may be processed to deduce position information by looking at the changes in RF level and phase caused by varying the local magnetic field using gradient coils.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] As these coils are rapidly switched during the excitation and response to perform a moving line scan, they create the characteristic repetitive noise of an MRI scan as the windings move slightly due to magnetostriction.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The contrast between different tissues is determined by the rate at which excited atoms return to the equilibrium state.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Exogenous contrast agents may be given to the person to make the image clearer.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI requires a magnetic field that is both strong and uniform to a few parts per million across the scan volume.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The field strength of the magnet is measured in teslas – and while the majority of systems operate at 1.5 T, commercial systems are available between 0.2 and 7 T.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 3T MRI systems, also called 3 Tesla MRIs, have stronger magnets than 1.5 systems and are considered better for images of organs and soft tissue.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Whole-body MRI systems for research applications operate in e.g.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Even higher field whole-body MRI systems e.g.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 14 T and beyond are in conceptual proposal or in engineering design.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most clinical magnets are superconducting magnets, which require liquid helium to keep them at low temperatures.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Lower field strengths can be achieved with permanent magnets, which are often used in "open" MRI scanners for claustrophobic patients.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Lower field strengths are also used in a portable MRI scanner approved by the FDA in 2020.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Each tissue returns to its equilibrium state after excitation by the independent relaxation processes of T1 (spin-lattice; that is, magnetization in the same direction as the static magnetic field) and T2 (spin-spin; transverse to the static magnetic field).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To create a T1-weighted image, magnetization is allowed to recover before measuring the MR signal by changing the repetition time (TR).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This image weighting is useful for assessing the cerebral cortex, identifying fatty tissue, characterizing focal liver lesions, and in general, obtaining morphological information, as well as for post-contrast imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To create a T2-weighted image, magnetization is allowed to decay before measuring the MR signal by changing the echo time (TE).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This image weighting is useful for detecting edema and inflammation, revealing white matter lesions, and assessing zonal anatomy in the prostate and uterus.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The information from MRI scans comes in the form of image contrasts based on differences in the rate of relaxation of nuclear spins following their perturbation by an oscillating magnetic field (in the form of radiofrequency pulses through the sample).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The relaxation rates are a measure of the time it takes for a signal to decay back to an equilibrium state from either the longitudinal or transverse plane.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetization builds up along the z-axis in the presence of a magnetic field, B0, such that the magnetic dipoles in the sample will, on average, align with the z-axis summing to a total magnetization Mz.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This magnetization along z is defined as the equilibrium magnetization; magnetization is defined as the sum of all magnetic dipoles in a sample.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Following the equilibrium magnetization, a 90° radiofrequency (RF) pulse flips the direction of the magnetization vector in the xy-plane, and is then switched off.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The initial magnetic field B0, however, is still applied.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Thus, the spin magnetization vector will slowly return from the xy-plane back to the equilibrium state.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The time it takes for the magnetization vector to return to its equilibrium value, Mz, is referred to as the longitudinal relaxation time, T1.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Subsequently, the rate at which this happens is simply the reciprocal of the relaxation time: ${\frac {1}{T_{1}}}=R_{1}$ .
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Similarly, the time in which it takes for Mxy to return to zero is T2, with the rate ${\frac {1}{T_{2}}}=R_{2}$ .
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetization as a function of time is defined by the Bloch equations.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] T1 and T2 values are dependent on the chemical environment of the sample; hence their utility in MRI.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Soft tissue and muscle tissue relax at different rates, yielding the image contrast in a typical scan.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI has a wide range of applications in medical diagnosis and around 50,000 scanners are estimated to be in use worldwide.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI affects diagnosis and treatment in many specialties although the effect on improved health outcomes is disputed in certain cases.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI is the investigation of choice in the preoperative staging of rectal and prostate cancer and has a role in the diagnosis, staging, and follow-up of other tumors, as well as for determining areas of tissue for sampling in biobanking.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI is the investigative tool of choice for neurological cancers over CT, as it offers better visualization of the posterior cranial fossa, containing the brainstem and the cerebellum.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The contrast provided between grey and white matter makes MRI the best choice for many conditions of the central nervous system, including demyelinating diseases, dementia, cerebrovascular disease, infectious diseases, Alzheimer's disease and epilepsy.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since multiple images are taken milliseconds apart, it can show how the brain responds to different stimuli, enabling researchers to study both functional and structural brain abnormalities in psychological disorders.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI also is used in guided stereotactic surgery and radiosurgery for treatment of intracranial tumors, arteriovenous malformations, and other surgically treatable conditions using a device known as the N-localizer.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] New tools that implement artificial intelligence in healthcare have demonstrated higher image quality and morphometric analysis in neuroimaging with the application of a denoising system.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] More broadly, deep learning has been applied to accelerate MRI acquisition itself by reconstructing diagnostic-quality images from undersampled k-space data.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] These methods have since been adopted as a clinical standard for accelerated MRI at several major medical centers.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The record for the highest spatial resolution of a whole intact brain (postmortem) is 100 microns, from Massachusetts General Hospital.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The data was published in *Nature* in October 2019.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Though MRI is used widely in research on mental disabilities, based on a 2024 systematic literature review and meta analysis commissioned by the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI), available research using MRI scans to diagnose ADHD showed great variability.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The authors conclude that MRI cannot be reliably used to assist in making a clinical diagnosis of ADHD.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Cardiac MRI is complementary to other imaging techniques, such as echocardiography, cardiac CT, and nuclear medicine.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] It can be used to assess the structure and the function of the heart.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Its applications include assessment of myocardial ischemia and viability, cardiomyopathies, myocarditis, iron overload, vascular diseases, and congenital heart disease.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Applications in the musculoskeletal system include spinal imaging, assessment of joint disease, and soft tissue tumors.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI techniques can also be used for diagnostic imaging of systemic muscle diseases including genetic muscle diseases.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Swallowing movements of the throat and esophagus can cause motion artifacts over the imaged spine.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Therefore, a saturation pulse applied over this region can help to avoid these artifacts.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Motion artifacts arising due to the pumping of the heart can be reduced by timing the MRI pulse according to heart cycles.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Blood vessel flow artifacts can be reduced by applying saturation pulses above and below the region of interest.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Hepatobiliary MRI is used to detect and characterize lesions of the liver, pancreas, and bile ducts.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Focal or diffuse disorders of the liver may be evaluated using diffusion-weighted, opposed-phase imaging and dynamic contrast enhancement sequences.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Extracellular contrast agents are used widely in liver MRI, and newer hepatobiliary contrast agents also provide the opportunity to perform functional biliary imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Anatomical imaging of the bile ducts is achieved by using a heavily T2-weighted sequence in magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Functional imaging of the pancreas is performed following administration of secretin.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MR enterography provides non-invasive assessment of inflammatory bowel disease and small bowel tumors.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MR-colonography may play a role in the detection of large polyps in patients at increased risk of colorectal cancer.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic resonance angiography (MRA) generates pictures of the arteries to evaluate them for stenosis (abnormal narrowing) or aneurysms (vessel wall dilatations, at risk of rupture).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRA is often used to evaluate the arteries of the neck and brain, the thoracic and abdominal aorta, the renal arteries, and the legs (called a "run-off").
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Techniques involving phase accumulation (known as phase contrast angiography) can also be used to generate flow velocity maps easily and accurately.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic resonance venography (MRV) is a similar procedure that is used to image veins.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In this method, the tissue is now excited inferiorly, while the signal is gathered in the plane immediately superior to the excitation plane—thus imaging the venous blood that recently moved from the excited plane.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI for imaging anatomical structures or blood flow do not require contrast agents since the varying properties of the tissues or blood provide natural contrasts.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, for more specific types of imaging, exogenous contrast agents may be given intravenously, orally, or intra-articularly.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most contrast agents are either paramagnetic (e.g.: gadolinium, manganese, europium), and are used to shorten T1 in the tissue they accumulate in, or super-paramagnetic (SPIONs), and are used to shorten T2 and T2* in healthy tissue reducing its signal intensity (negative contrast agents).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The most commonly used intravenous contrast agents are based on chelates of gadolinium, which is highly paramagnetic.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In general, these agents have proved safer than the iodinated contrast agents used in X-ray radiography or CT.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Anaphylactoid reactions are rare, occurring in approx.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Of particular interest is the lower incidence of nephrotoxicity, compared with iodinated agents, when given at usual doses—this has made contrast-enhanced MRI scanning an option for patients with renal impairment, who would otherwise not be able to undergo contrast-enhanced CT.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Gadolinium-based contrast reagents are typically octadentate complexes of gadolinium(III).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The complex is very stable (log K > 20) so that, in use, the concentration of the un-complexed Gd3+ ions should be below the toxicity limit.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The 9th place in the metal ion's coordination sphere is occupied by a water molecule which exchanges rapidly with water molecules in the reagent molecule's immediate environment, affecting the magnetic resonance relaxation time.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In December 2017, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in the United States announced in a drug safety communication that new warnings were to be included on all gadolinium-based contrast agents (GBCAs).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The FDA also called for increased patient education and requiring gadolinium contrast vendors to conduct additional animal and clinical studies to assess the safety of these agents.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Although gadolinium agents have proved useful for patients with kidney impairment, in patients with severe kidney failure requiring dialysis there is a risk of a rare but serious illness, nephrogenic systemic fibrosis, which may be linked to the use of certain gadolinium-containing agents.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The most frequently linked is gadodiamide, but other agents have been linked too.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Although a causal link has not been definitively established, current guidelines in the United States are that dialysis patients should only receive gadolinium agents where essential and that dialysis should be performed as soon as possible after the scan to remove the agent from the body promptly.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In Europe, where more gadolinium-containing agents are available, a classification of agents according to potential risks has been released.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In 2008, a new contrast agent named gadoxetate, brand name Eovist (US) or Primovist (EU), was approved for diagnostic use: This has the theoretical benefit of a dual excretion path.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] An MRI sequence is a particular setting of radiofrequency pulses and gradients, resulting in a particular image appearance.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The T1 and T2 weighting can also be described as MRI sequences.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This table does not include uncommon and experimental sequences.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS) is used to measure the levels of different metabolites in body tissues, which can be achieved through a variety of single voxel or imaging-based techniques.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The MR signal produces a spectrum of resonances that corresponds to different molecular arrangements of the isotope being "excited".
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This signature is used to diagnose certain metabolic disorders, especially those affecting the brain, and to provide information on tumor metabolism.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic resonance spectroscopic imaging (MRSI) combines both spectroscopic and imaging methods to produce spatially localized spectra from within the sample or patient.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The spatial resolution is much lower (limited by the available SNR), but the spectra in each voxel contains information about many metabolites.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Because the available signal is used to encode spatial and spectral information, MRSI requires high SNR achievable only at higher field strengths (3 T and above).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The high procurement and maintenance costs of MRI with extremely high field strengths inhibit their popularity.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, recent compressed sensing-based software algorithms (*e.g.*, SAMV) have been proposed to achieve super-resolution without requiring such high field strengths.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Real-time magnetic resonance imaging (RT-MRI) refers to the continuous monitoring of moving objects in real time.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Traditionally, real-time MRI was possible only with low image quality or low temporal resolution.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] An iterative reconstruction algorithm removed limitations.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Radial FLASH MRI (real-time) yields a temporal resolution of 20 to 30 milliseconds for images with an in-plane resolution of 1.5 to 2.0 mm.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Real-time MRI adds information about diseases of the joints and the heart.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In many cases MRI examinations become easier and more comfortable for patients, especially for the patients who cannot calm their breathing or who have arrhythmia.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Balanced steady-state free precession (bSSFP) imaging gives better image contrast between the blood pool and myocardium than FLASH MRI, at the cost of severe banding artifact when B0 inhomogeneity is strong.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The lack of harmful effects on the patient and the operator make MRI well-suited for interventional radiology, where the images produced by an MRI scanner guide minimally invasive procedures.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Such procedures use no ferromagnetic instruments.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] A specialized growing subset of interventional MRI is intraoperative MRI, in which an MRI is used in surgery.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Some specialized MRI systems allow imaging concurrent with the surgical procedure.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] More typically, the surgical procedure is temporarily interrupted so that MRI can assess the success of the procedure or guide subsequent surgical work.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In guided therapy, high-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU) beams are focused on a tissue, that are controlled using MR thermal imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Due to the high energy at the focus, the temperature rises to above 65 °C (150 °F) which completely destroys the tissue.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This technology can achieve precise ablation of diseased tissue.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MR imaging provides a three-dimensional view of the target tissue, allowing for the precise focusing of ultrasound energy.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The MR imaging provides quantitative, real-time, thermal images of the treated area.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This allows the physician to ensure that the temperature generated during each cycle of ultrasound energy is sufficient to cause thermal ablation within the desired tissue and if not, to adapt the parameters to ensure effective treatment.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Hydrogen has the most frequently imaged nucleus in MRI because it is present in biological tissues in great abundance, and because its high gyromagnetic ratio gives a strong signal.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, any nucleus with a net nuclear spin could potentially be imaged with MRI.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Such nuclei include deuterium, helium-3, lithium-7, carbon-13, fluorine-19, oxygen-17, sodium-23, phosphorus-31 and xenon-129.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 2H, 23Na and 31P are naturally abundant in the body, so they can be imaged directly.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Naturally abundant deuterium at the concentration of around 15mM can be imaged, but suffers from low gamma sensitivity and quadripolar Relaxation (NMR).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Deuterium imaging however has a sparse chemical shift spectrum making it possible to develop tailored multiband selective RF pulses for metabolite selective imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Thus, metabolic imaging, similar to what's done with Carbon-13 is possible with Deuterium metabolic imaging (DMI) for insights into vivo metabolic processes.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] As well, the short T2 of deuterium allows it to be signal averaged rapidly, making up for some of its physical shortcomings.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Gaseous isotopes such as 3He or 129Xe must be hyperpolarized and then inhaled as their nuclear density is too low to yield a useful signal under normal conditions.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 17O and 19F can be administered in sufficient quantities in liquid form (e.g.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 17O-water) that hyperpolarization is not a necessity.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Using helium or xenon has the advantage of reduced background noise, and therefore increased contrast for the image itself, because these elements are not normally present in biological tissues.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In principle, heteronuclear magnetization transfer MRI could be used to detect the presence or absence of specific chemical bonds.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Multinuclear imaging is primarily a research technique at present.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, potential applications include functional imaging and imaging of organs poorly seen on 1H MRI (e.g., lungs and bones) or as alternative contrast agents.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Inhaled hyperpolarized 3He can be used to image the distribution of air spaces within the lungs.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Injectable solutions containing 13C or stabilized bubbles of hyperpolarized 129Xe have been studied as contrast agents for angiography and perfusion imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] 31P can potentially provide information on bone density and structure, as well as functional imaging of the brain.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Multinuclear imaging holds the potential to chart the distribution of lithium in the human brain, this element finding use as an important drug for those with conditions such as bipolar disorder.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI has the advantages of having very high spatial resolution and is very adept at morphological imaging and functional imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI does have several disadvantages though.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] First, MRI has a sensitivity of around 10−3 mol/L to 10−5 mol/L, which, compared to other types of imaging, can be very limiting.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This problem stems from the fact that the population difference between the nuclear spin states is very small at room temperature.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] For example, at 1.5 teslas, a typical field strength for clinical MRI, the difference between high and low energy states is approximately 9 molecules per 2 million.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Improvements to increase MR sensitivity include increasing magnetic field strength and hyperpolarization via optical pumping or dynamic nuclear polarization.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] There are also a variety of signal amplification schemes based on chemical exchange that increase sensitivity.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To achieve molecular imaging of disease biomarkers using MRI, targeted MRI contrast agents with high specificity and high relaxivity (sensitivity) are required.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To date, many studies have been devoted to developing targeted-MRI contrast agents to achieve molecular imaging by MRI.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Commonly, peptides, antibodies, or small ligands, and small protein domains, such as HER-2 affibodies, have been applied to achieve targeting.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] To enhance the sensitivity of the contrast agents, these targeting moieties are usually linked to high payload MRI contrast agents or MRI contrast agents with high relaxivities.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] A new class of gene targeting MR contrast agents has been introduced to show gene action of unique mRNA and gene transcription factor proteins.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] These new contrast agents can trace cells with unique mRNA, microRNA and virus; tissue response to inflammation in living brains.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The MR reports change in gene expression with positive correlation to TaqMan analysis, optical and electron microscopy.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] It takes time to gather MRI data using sequential applications of magnetic field gradients.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Even for the most streamlined of MRI sequences, there are physical and physiologic limits to the rate of gradient switching.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Parallel MRI circumvents these limits by gathering some portion of the data simultaneously, rather than in a traditional sequential fashion.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This is accomplished using arrays of radiofrequency (RF) detector coils, each with a different 'view' of the body.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] A reduced set of gradient steps is applied, and the remaining spatial information is filled in by combining signals from various coils, based on their known spatial sensitivity patterns.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Parallel MRI may be used with most MRI sequences.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] After a number of early suggestions for using arrays of detectors to accelerate imaging went largely unremarked in the MRI field, parallel imaging saw widespread development and application following the introduction of the simultaneous acquisition of spatial harmonics (SMASH) technique in 1996–7.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The sensitivity encoding (SENSE) and generalized autocalibrating partially parallel acquisitions (GRAPPA) techniques are the parallel imaging methods in most common use today.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The advent of parallel MRI resulted in extensive research and development in image reconstruction and RF coil design, as well as in a rapid expansion of the number of receiver channels available on commercial MR systems.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Parallel MRI is now used routinely for MRI examinations in a wide range of body areas and clinical or research applications.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Deep learning approaches extend traditional acceleration methods by training neural networks on large datasets of paired undersampled and fully-sampled MRI scans, enabling image reconstruction at higher acceleration factors than classical parallel imaging alone.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Rather than relying on hand-crafted sparsity priors as in compressed sensing, these models learn reconstruction directly from data.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] One prominent approach, the end-to-end variational network (E2E-VarNet), combines sensitivity map estimation and iterative refinement in a fully learned pipeline, achieving state-of-the-art reconstruction quality on the fastMRI benchmark for both knee and brain MRI..
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The fastMRI initiative, a collaboration between Meta AI Research (FAIR) and NYU Langone Health, established the field's primary open benchmark by releasing over 1.5 million raw MRI measurements from knee, brain, and prostate scans in 2018.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Annual fastMRI challenges have benchmarked reconstruction quality across international research teams.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] A clinical interchangeability study confirmed that deep learning reconstruction at 4× acceleration produces images diagnostically equivalent to fully-sampled acquisitions for knee imaging at 3T, and these methods have since been adopted clinically at major medical centers.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most MRI focuses on qualitative interpretation of MR data by acquiring spatial maps of relative variations in signal strength which are "weighted" by certain parameters.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Quantitative methods instead attempt to determine spatial maps of accurate tissue relaxometry parameter values or magnetic field, or to measure the size of certain spatial features.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Quantitative MRI aims to increase the reproducibility of MR images and interpretations, but has historically require longer scan times.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Quantitative MRI (or qMRI) sometimes more specifically refers to multi-parametric quantitative MRI, the mapping of multiple tissue relaxometry parameters in a single imaging session.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Efforts to make multi-parametric quantitative MRI faster have produced sequences which map multiple parameters simultaneously, either by building separate encoding methods for each parameter into the sequence, or by fitting MR signal evolution to a multi-parameter model.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Traditional MRI generates poor images of lung tissue because there are fewer water molecules with protons that can be excited by the magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Using hyperpolarized gas an MRI scan can identify ventilation defects in the lungs.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Before the scan, a patient is asked to inhale hyperpolarized xenon mixed with a buffer gas of helium or nitrogen.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The resulting lung images are much higher quality than with traditional MRI.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI is, in general, a safe technique, although injuries may occur as a result of failed safety procedures or human error.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Contraindications to MRI include most cochlear implants and cardiac pacemakers, shrapnel, and metallic foreign bodies in the eyes.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic resonance imaging in pregnancy appears to be safe, at least during the second and third trimesters if done without contrast agents.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since MRI does not use any ionizing radiation, its use is generally favored in preference to CT when either modality could yield the same information.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Some patients experience claustrophobia and may require sedation or shorter MRI protocols.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Amplitude and rapid switching of gradient coils during image acquisition may cause peripheral nerve stimulation.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI uses powerful magnets and can therefore cause magnetic materials to move at great speeds, posing a projectile risk, and may cause fatal accidents.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, as millions of MRIs are performed globally each year, fatalities are extremely rare.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI machines can produce loud noise, up to 120 dB(A).
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This can cause hearing loss, tinnitus and hyperacusis, so appropriate hearing protection is essential for anyone inside the MRI scanner room during the examination.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Medical societies issue guidelines for when physicians should use MRI on patients and recommend against overuse.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI can detect health problems or confirm a diagnosis, but medical societies often recommend that MRI not be the first procedure for creating a plan to diagnose or manage a patient's complaint.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] A common case is to use MRI to seek a cause of low back pain; the American College of Physicians, for example, recommends against imaging (including MRI) as unlikely to result in a positive outcome for the patient.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] An MRI artifact is a visual artifact, that is, an anomaly during visual representation.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Many different artifacts can occur during magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), some affecting the diagnostic quality, while others may be confused with pathology.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Artifacts can be classified as patient-related, signal processing-dependent and hardware (machine)-related.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI is used industrially mainly for routine analysis of chemicals.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] The nuclear magnetic resonance technique is also used, for example, to measure the ratio between water and fat in foods, monitoring of flow of corrosive fluids in pipes, or to study molecular structures such as catalysts.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Being non-invasive and non-damaging, MRI can be used to study the anatomy of plants, their water transportation processes and water balance.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] It is also applied to veterinary radiology for diagnostic purposes.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Outside this, its use in zoology is limited due to the high cost; but it can be used on many species.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In palaeontology it is used to examine the structure of fossils.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Forensic imaging provides graphic documentation of an autopsy, which manual autopsy does not.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] CT scanning provides quick whole-body imaging of skeletal and parenchymal alterations, whereas MR imaging gives better representation of soft tissue pathology.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] All that being said, MRI is more expensive, and more time-consuming to utilize.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Moreover, the quality of MR imaging deteriorates below 10 °C.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In 1971 at Stony Brook University, Paul Lauterbur applied magnetic field gradients in all three dimensions and a back-projection technique to create NMR images.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] He published the first images of two tubes of water in 1973 in the journal *Nature*, followed by the picture of a living animal, a clam, and in 1974 by the image of the thoracic cavity of a mouse.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Lauterbur called his imaging method zeugmatography, a term which was replaced by (N)MR imaging.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the late 1970s, physicists Peter Mansfield at the University of Nottingham and Lauterbur developed MRI-related techniques, like the echo-planar imaging (EPI) technique.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Raymond Damadian's work into nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) has been incorporated into MRI, having built one of the first scanners.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Advances in semiconductor technology were crucial to the development of practical MRI, which requires a large amount of computational power.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] This was made possible by the rapidly increasing number of transistors on a single integrated circuit chip.
[src:mri-physics/magnetic-resonance-imaging] Mansfield and Lauterbur were awarded the 2003 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their "discoveries concerning magnetic resonance imaging".
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] An **MRI pulse sequence** in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is a particular setting of pulse sequences and pulsed field gradients, resulting in a particular image appearance.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] A multiparametric MRI is a combination of two or more sequences, and/or including other specialized MRI configurations such as spectroscopy.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Proton density (PD)- weighted images are created by having a long repetition time (TR) and a short echo time (TE).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] On images of the brain, this sequence has a more pronounced distinction between grey matter (bright) and white matter (darker grey), but with little contrast between brain and CSF.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is very useful for the detection of arthropathy and injury.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] A *gradient echo sequence* does not use a 180 degrees RF pulse to make the spins of particles coherent.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Instead, it uses magnetic gradients to manipulate the spins, allowing the spins to dephase and rephase when required.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] After an excitation pulse, the spins are dephased, no signal is produced because the spins are not coherent.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] When the spins are rephased, they become coherent, and thus signal (or "echo") is generated to form images.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Unlike spin echo, gradient echo does not need to wait for transverse magnetisation to decay completely before initiating another sequence, thus it requires very short repetition times (TR), and therefore to acquire images in a short time.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] After echo is formed, some transverse magnetisations remains.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Manipulating gradients during this time will produce images with different contrast.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] For comparison purposes, the repetition time of a gradient echo sequence is of the order of 3 milliseconds, versus about 30 ms of a spin echo sequence.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Diffusion MRI measures the diffusion of water molecules in biological tissues.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Clinically, diffusion MRI is useful for the diagnoses of conditions (e.g., stroke) or neurological disorders (e.g., multiple sclerosis), and helps better understand the connectivity of white matter axons in the central nervous system.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] In an isotropic medium (inside a glass of water for example), water molecules naturally move randomly according to turbulence and Brownian motion.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] In biological tissues however, where the Reynolds number is low enough for laminar flow, the diffusion may be anisotropic.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] For example, a molecule inside the axon of a neuron has a low probability of crossing the myelin membrane.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Therefore, the molecule moves principally along the axis of the neural fiber.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] If it is known that molecules in a particular voxel diffuse principally in one direction, the assumption can be made that the majority of the fibers in this area are parallel to that direction.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The recent development of diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) enables diffusion to be measured in multiple directions, and the fractional anisotropy in each direction to be calculated for each voxel.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This enables researchers to make brain maps of fiber directions to examine the connectivity of different regions in the brain (using tractography) or to examine areas of neural degeneration and demyelination in diseases like multiple sclerosis.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Another application of diffusion MRI is diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Following an ischemic stroke, DWI is highly sensitive to the changes occurring in the lesion.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is speculated that increases in restriction (barriers) to water diffusion, as a result of cytotoxic edema (cellular swelling), is responsible for the increase in signal on a DWI scan.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The DWI enhancement appears within 5–10 minutes of the onset of stroke symptoms (as compared to computed tomography, which often does not detect changes of acute infarct for up to 4–6 hours) and remains for up to two weeks.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Coupled with imaging of cerebral perfusion, researchers can highlight regions of "perfusion/diffusion mismatch" that may indicate regions capable of salvage by reperfusion therapy.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Like many other specialized applications, this technique is usually coupled with a fast image acquisition sequence, such as echo planar imaging sequence.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The acquired data is then postprocessed to obtain perfusion maps with different parameters, such as BV (blood volume), BF (blood flow), MTT (mean transit time) and TTP (time to peak).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] In cerebral infarction, the penumbra has decreased perfusion.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Another MRI sequence, diffusion-weighted MRI, estimates the amount of tissue that is already necrotic, and the combination of those sequences can therefore be used to estimate the amount of brain tissue that is salvageable by thrombolysis and/or thrombectomy.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Functional MRI (fMRI) measures signal changes in the brain that are due to changing neural activity.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is used to understand how different parts of the brain respond to external stimuli or passive activity in a resting state, and has applications in behavioral and cognitive research, and in planning neurosurgery of eloquent brain areas.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Researchers use statistical methods to construct a 3-D parametric map of the brain indicating the regions of the cortex that demonstrate a significant change in activity in response to the task.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Compared to anatomical T1W imaging, the brain is scanned at lower spatial resolution but at a higher temporal resolution (typically once every 2–3 seconds).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Increases in neural activity cause changes in the MR signal via *T** 2 changes; this mechanism is referred to as the BOLD (blood-oxygen-level dependent) effect.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Increased neural activity causes an increased demand for oxygen, and the vascular system actually overcompensates for this, increasing the amount of oxygenated hemoglobin relative to deoxygenated hemoglobin.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Because deoxygenated hemoglobin attenuates the MR signal, the vascular response leads to a signal increase that is related to the neural activity.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The precise nature of the relationship between neural activity and the BOLD signal is a subject of current research.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The BOLD effect also allows for the generation of high resolution 3D maps of the venous vasculature within neural tissue.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] While BOLD signal analysis is the most common method employed for neuroscience studies in human subjects, the flexible nature of MR imaging provides means to sensitize the signal to other aspects of the blood supply.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Alternative techniques employ arterial spin labeling (ASL) or weighting the MRI signal by cerebral blood flow (CBF) and cerebral blood volume (CBV).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The CBV method requires injection of a class of MRI contrast agents that are now in human clinical trials.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Because this method has been shown to be far more sensitive than the BOLD technique in preclinical studies, it may potentially expand the role of fMRI in clinical applications.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The CBF method provides more quantitative information than the BOLD signal, albeit at a significant loss of detection sensitivity.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Magnetic resonance angiography (*MRA*) is a group of techniques based to image blood vessels.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Magnetic resonance angiography is used to generate images of arteries (and less commonly veins) in order to evaluate them for stenosis (abnormal narrowing), occlusions, aneurysms (vessel wall dilatations, at risk of rupture) or other abnormalities.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] MRA is often used to evaluate the arteries of the neck and brain, the thoracic and abdominal aorta, the renal arteries, and the legs (the latter exam is often referred to as a "run-off").
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Phase contrast MRI (PC-MRI) is used to measure flow velocities in the body.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is used mainly to measure blood flow in the heart and throughout the body.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] PC-MRI may be considered a method of magnetic resonance velocimetry.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Since modern PC-MRI typically is time-resolved, it also may be referred to as 4-D imaging (three spatial dimensions plus time).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI) is a new type of contrast in MRI different from spin density, *T*1, or *T*2 imaging.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This method exploits the susceptibility differences between tissues and uses a fully velocity-compensated, three-dimensional, RF-spoiled, high-resolution, 3D-gradient echo scan.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This special data acquisition and image processing produces an enhanced contrast magnitude image very sensitive to venous blood, hemorrhage and iron storage.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is used to enhance the detection and diagnosis of tumors, vascular and neurovascular diseases (stroke and hemorrhage), multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's, and also detects traumatic brain injuries that may not be diagnosed using other methods.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Magnetization transfer (MT) is a technique to enhance image contrast in certain applications of MRI.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Bound protons are associated with proteins and as they have a very short T2 decay they do not normally contribute to image contrast.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] However, because these protons have a broad resonance peak they can be excited by a radiofrequency pulse that has no effect on free protons.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Their excitation increases image contrast by transfer of saturated spins from the bound pool into the free pool, thereby reducing the signal of free water.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This homonuclear magnetization transfer provides an indirect measurement of macromolecular content in tissue.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Implementation of homonuclear magnetization transfer involves choosing suitable frequency offsets and pulse shapes to saturate the bound spins sufficiently strongly, within the safety limits of specific absorption rate for MRI.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The most common use of this technique is for suppression of background signal in time of flight MR angiography.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] There are also applications in neuroimaging particularly in the characterization of white matter lesions in multiple sclerosis.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Fat suppression is useful for example to distinguish active inflammation in the intestines from fat deposition such as can be caused by long-standing (but possibly inactive) inflammatory bowel disease, but also obesity, chemotherapy and celiac disease.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Without fat suppression techniques, fat and fluid will have similar signal intensities on fast spin-echo sequences.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This method exploits the paramagnetic properties of neuromelanin and can be used to visualize the substantia nigra and the locus coeruleus.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is used to detect the atrophy of these nuclei in Parkinson's disease and other parkinsonisms, and also detects signal intensity changes in major depressive disorder and schizophrenia.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The following sequences are not commonly used clinically, and/or are at an experimental stage.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] T1 rho (T1ρ) is an experimental MRI sequence that may be used in musculoskeletal imaging.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] Molecules have a kinetic energy that is a function of the temperature and is expressed as translational and rotational motions, and by collisions between molecules.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] The moving dipoles disturb the magnetic field but are often extremely rapid so that the average effect over a long time-scale may be zero.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] However, depending on the time-scale, the interactions between the dipoles do not always average away.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] At the slowest extreme the interaction time is effectively infinite and occurs where there are large, stationary field disturbances (e.g., a metallic implant).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] In this case the loss of coherence is described as a "static dephasing".
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] T2* is a measure of the loss of coherence in an ensemble of spins that includes all interactions (including static dephasing).
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] T2 is a measure of the loss of coherence that excludes static dephasing, using an RF pulse to reverse the slowest types of dipolar interaction.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] There is in fact a continuum of interaction time-scales in a given biological sample, and the properties of the refocusing RF pulse can be tuned to refocus more than just static dephasing.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] In general, the rate of decay of an ensemble of spins is a function of the interaction times and also the power of the RF pulse.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] This type of decay, occurring under the influence of RF, is known as T1ρ.
[src:mri-physics/mri-pulse-sequence] It is similar to T2 decay but with some slower dipolar interactions refocused, as well as static interactions, hence T1ρ≥T2.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Contrast agents may be injected intravenously or into a joint to enhance the image and facilitate diagnosis.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Unlike CT scans and X-rays, MRI does not use ionizing radiation and is therefore considered a safe procedure, making it suitable for use in children and for repeated examinations.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Patients with specific non-ferromagnetic metal implants, cochlear implants, and cardiac pacemakers nowadays may also have an MRI in spite of effects of the strong magnetic fields.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This does not apply on older devices, and details for medical professionals are provided by the device's manufacturer.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Certain atomic nuclei are able to absorb and emit radio frequency energy when placed in an external magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In clinical and research MRI, hydrogen atoms are most often used to generate a detectable radio-frequency signal that is received by antennas close to the anatomy being examined.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Hydrogen atoms are naturally abundant in people and other biological organisms, particularly in water and fat.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Pulses of radio waves excite the nuclear spin energy transition, and magnetic field gradients localize the signal in space.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When inside the magnetic field (*B*0) of the scanner, the magnetic moments of the protons align to be either parallel or anti-parallel to the direction of the field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] While each individual proton can only have one of two alignments, the collection of protons appear to behave as though they can have any alignment.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most protons align parallel to *B*0 as this is a lower energy state.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] A radio frequency pulse is then applied, which can excite protons from parallel to anti-parallel alignment; only the latter are relevant to the rest of the discussion.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In response to the force bringing them back to their equilibrium orientation, the protons undergo a rotating motion (precession), much like a spun wheel under the effect of gravity.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The protons will return to the low energy state by the process of spin-lattice relaxation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This appears as a changing magnetic flux, which yields a changing voltage in the receiver coils to give a signal.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The frequency at which a proton or group of protons in a voxel resonates depends on the strength of the local magnetic field around the proton or group of protons, a stronger field corresponds to a larger energy difference and higher frequency photons.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] By applying additional magnetic fields (gradients) that vary linearly over space, specific slices to be imaged can be selected, and an image is obtained by taking the 2-D Fourier transform of the spatial frequencies of the signal (*k*-space).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Due to the magnetic Lorentz force from *B*0 on the current flowing in the gradient coils, the gradient coils will try to move producing loud knocking sounds, for which patients require hearing protection.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The MRI scanner was developed from 1975 to 1977 at the University of Nottingham by Prof Raymond Andrew FRS FRSE following from his research into nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The full body scanner was created in 1978.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Subatomic particles have the quantum mechanical property of spin.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Certain nuclei such as 1H (protons), 2H, 3He, 23Na or 31P, have a non–zero spin and therefore a magnetic moment.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the case of the so-called spin-1⁄2 nuclei, such as 1H, there are two spin states, sometimes referred to as *up* and *down*.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Nuclei such as 12C have no unpaired neutrons or protons, and no net spin; however, the isotope 13C does.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When these spins are placed in a strong external magnetic field they precess around an axis along the direction of the field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Protons align in two energy eigenstates (the Zeeman effect): one low-energy and one high-energy, which are separated by a very small splitting energy.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Quantum mechanics is required to accurately model the behaviour of a single proton.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, classical mechanics can be used to describe the behaviour of an ensemble of protons adequately.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] As with other spin $1/2$ particles, whenever the spin of a single proton is measured it can only have one of two results commonly called parallel and anti-parallel.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When we discuss the state of a proton or protons we are referring to the wave function of that proton which is a linear combination of the parallel and anti-parallel states.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the presence of the magnetic field, **B**0, the protons will appear to precess at the Larmor frequency determined by the particle's gyro-magnetic ratio and the strength of the field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The static fields used most commonly in MRI cause precession which corresponds to a radiofrequency (RF) photon.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The net longitudinal magnetization in thermodynamic equilibrium is due to a tiny excess of protons in the lower energy state.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This gives a net polarization that is parallel to the external field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Application of an RF pulse can tip this net polarization vector sideways (with, i.e., a so-called 90° pulse), or even reverse it (with a so-called 180° pulse).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] An RF pulse produces detectable transverse magnetization by rotating the bulk magnetization vector that exists at thermal equilibrium and not by bringing spins into phase coherence as is sometimes stated in literature.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The recovery of longitudinal magnetization is called longitudinal or *T*1 relaxation and occurs exponentially with a time constant *T*1.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The loss of phase coherence in the transverse plane is called transverse or *T*2 relaxation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] *T*1 is thus associated with the enthalpy of the spin system, or the number of nuclei with parallel versus anti-parallel spin.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] *T*2 on the other hand is associated with the entropy of the system, or the number of nuclei in phase.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When the radio frequency pulse is turned off, the transverse vector component produces an oscillating magnetic field which induces a small current in the receiver coil.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This signal is called the free induction decay (FID).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In an idealized nuclear magnetic resonance experiment, the FID decays approximately exponentially with a time constant *T*2.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, in practical MRI there are small differences in the static magnetic field at different spatial locations ("inhomogeneities") that cause the Larmor frequency to vary across the body.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This creates destructive interference, which shortens the FID.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The time constant for the observed decay of the FID is called the *T** 2 relaxation time, and is always shorter than *T*2.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] At the same time, the longitudinal magnetization starts to recover exponentially with a time constant *T*1 which is much larger than *T*2 (see below).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In MRI, the static magnetic field is augmented by a field gradient coil to vary across the scanned region, so that different spatial locations become associated with different precession frequencies.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Only those regions where the field is such that the precession frequencies match the RF frequency will experience excitation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Usually, these field gradients are modulated to sweep across the region to be scanned, and it is the almost infinite variety of RF and gradient pulse sequences that gives MRI its versatility.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The whole process can be repeated when some *T*1-relaxation has occurred and the thermal equilibrium of the spins has been more or less restored.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The **repetition time** (TR) is the time between two successive excitations of the same slice.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typically, in soft tissues *T*1 is around one second while *T*2 and *T** 2 are a few tens of milliseconds.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, these values can vary widely between different tissues, as well as between different external magnetic fields.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This behavior is one factor giving MRI its tremendous soft tissue contrast.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] MRI contrast agents, such as those containing Gadolinium(III) work by altering (shortening) the relaxation parameters, especially *T*1.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Although each of these schemes is occasionally used in specialist applications, the majority of MR Images today are created either by the two-dimensional Fourier transform (2DFT) technique with slice selection, or by the three-dimensional Fourier transform (3DFT) technique.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] What follows here is a description of the 2DFT technique with slice selection.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The 3DFT technique is rather similar except that there is no slice selection and phase-encoding is performed in two separate directions.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Another scheme which is sometimes used, especially in brain scanning or where images are needed very rapidly, is called echo-planar imaging (EPI): In this case, each RF excitation is followed by a train of gradient echoes with different spatial encoding.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Multiplexed-EPI is even faster, e.g., for whole brain functional MRI (fMRI) or diffusion MRI.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Image contrast is created by differences in the strength of the NMR signal recovered from different locations within the sample.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This depends upon the relative density of excited nuclei (usually water protons), on differences in relaxation times (*T*1, *T*2, and *T** 2) of those nuclei after the pulse sequence, and often on other parameters discussed under specialized MR scans.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Contrast in most MR images is actually a mixture of all these effects, but careful design of the imaging pulse sequence allows one contrast mechanism to be emphasized while the others are minimized.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The ability to choose different contrast mechanisms gives MRI tremendous flexibility.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the brain, *T*1-weighting causes the nerve connections of white matter to appear white, and the congregations of neurons of gray matter to appear gray, while cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) appears dark.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The contrast of white matter, gray matter and cerebrospinal fluid is reversed using *T*2 or *T** 2 imaging, whereas proton-density-weighted imaging provides little contrast in healthy subjects.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Additionally, functional parameters such as cerebral blood flow (CBF), cerebral blood volume (CBV) or blood oxygenation can affect *T*1, *T*2, and *T** 2 and so can be encoded with suitable pulse sequences.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In some situations it is not possible to generate enough image contrast to adequately show the anatomy or pathology of interest by adjusting the imaging parameters alone, in which case a contrast agent may be administered.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This can be as simple as water, taken orally, for imaging the stomach and small bowel.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, most contrast agents used in MRI are selected for their specific magnetic properties.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most commonly, a paramagnetic contrast agent (usually a gadolinium compound) is given.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Gadolinium-enhanced tissues and fluids appear extremely bright on *T*1-weighted images.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This provides high sensitivity for detection of vascular tissues (e.g., tumors) and permits assessment of brain perfusion (e.g., in stroke).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] There have been concerns raised recently regarding the toxicity of gadolinium-based contrast agents and their impact on persons with impaired kidney function.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] More recently, superparamagnetic contrast agents, e.g., iron oxide nanoparticles, have become available.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] These agents appear very dark on *T** 2-weighted images and may be used for liver imaging, as normal liver tissue retains the agent, but abnormal areas (e.g., scars, tumors) do not.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] They can also be taken orally, to improve visualization of the gastrointestinal tract, and to prevent water in the gastrointestinal tract from obscuring other organs (e.g., the pancreas).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Diamagnetic agents such as barium sulfate have also been studied for potential use in the gastrointestinal tract, but are less frequently used.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In 1983, Ljunggren and Twieg independently introduced the *k*-space formalism, a technique that proved invaluable in unifying different MR imaging techniques.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] They showed that the demodulated MR signal *S*(*t*) generated by the interaction between an ensemble of freely precessing nuclear spins in the presence of a linear magnetic field gradient *G* and a receiver-coil equals the Fourier transform of the effective spin density, $\rho ({\vec {x}})$ .
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In other words, as time progresses the signal traces out a trajectory in *k*-space with the velocity vector of the trajectory proportional to the vector of the applied magnetic field gradient.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] From the basic *k*-space formula, it follows immediately that we reconstruct an image $I({\vec {x}})$ by taking the inverse Fourier transform of the sampled data, viz.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Using the *k*-space formalism, a number of seemingly complex ideas became simple.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] For example, it becomes very easy (for physicists, in particular) to understand the role of phase encoding (the so-called spin-warp method).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In a standard spin echo or gradient echo scan, where the readout (or view) gradient is constant (e.g., *G*), a single line of *k*-space is scanned per RF excitation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When the phase encoding gradient is zero, the line scanned is the *k*x axis.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When a non-zero phase-encoding pulse is added in between the RF excitation and the commencement of the readout gradient, this line moves up or down in *k*-space, i.e., we scan the line *k*y=constant.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The *k*-space formalism also makes it very easy to compare different scanning techniques.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In single-shot EPI, all of *k*-space is scanned in a single shot, following either a sinusoidal or zig-zag trajectory.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since alternating lines of *k*-space are scanned in opposite directions, this must be taken into account in the reconstruction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Multi-shot EPI and fast spin echo techniques acquire only part of *k*-space per excitation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In each shot, a different interleaved segment is acquired, and the shots are repeated until *k*-space is sufficiently well-covered.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since the data at the center of *k*-space represent lower spatial frequencies than the data at the edges of *k*-space, the *T*E value for the center of *k*-space determines the image's *T*2 contrast.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The importance of the center of *k*-space in determining image contrast can be exploited in more advanced imaging techniques.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] One such technique is spiral acquisition—a rotating magnetic field gradient is applied, causing the trajectory in *k*-space to spiral out from the center to the edge.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Due to *T*2 and *T** 2 decay the signal is greatest at the start of the acquisition, hence acquiring the center of *k*-space first improves contrast to noise ratio (CNR) when compared to conventional zig-zag acquisitions, especially in the presence of rapid movement.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the timing diagram, the horizontal axis represents time.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The vertical axis represents: (top row) amplitude of radio frequency pulses; (middle rows) amplitudes of the three orthogonal magnetic field gradient pulses; and (bottom row) receiver analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Radio frequencies are transmitted at the Larmor frequency of the nuclide to be imaged.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] For example, for 1H in a magnetic field of 1 T, a frequency of 42.5781 MHz would be employed.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Where negative-going gradient pulses are shown, they represent reversal of the gradient direction, i.e., right-to-left, back-to-front or toe-to-head.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] For human scanning, gradient strengths of 1–100mT/m are employed: Higher gradient strengths permit better resolution and faster imaging.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The pulse sequence shown here would produce a transverse (axial) image.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The first part of the pulse sequence, SS, achieves "slice selection".
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] A shaped pulse (shown here with a sinc modulation) causes a 90° nutation of longitudinal nuclear magnetization within a slab, or slice, creating transverse magnetization.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The second part of the pulse sequence, PE, imparts a phase shift upon the slice-selected nuclear magnetization, varying with its location in the Y direction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The third part of the pulse sequence, another slice selection (of the same slice) uses another shaped pulse to cause a 180° rotation of transverse nuclear magnetization within the slice.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This transverse magnetisation refocuses to form a spin echo at a time *T*E.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] During the spin echo, a frequency-encoding (FE) or readout gradient is applied, making the resonant frequency of the nuclear magnetization vary with its location in the X direction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The signal is sampled *n*FE times by the ADC during this period, as represented by the vertical lines.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typically *n*FE of between 128 and 512 samples are taken.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The longitudinal magnetisation is then allowed to recover somewhat and after a time *T*R the whole sequence is repeated *n*PE times, but with the phase-encoding gradient incremented (indicated by the horizontal hatching in the green gradient block).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typically *n*PE of between 128 and 512 repetitions are made.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The negative-going lobes in *G*X and *G*Z are imposed to ensure that, at time *T*E (the spin echo maximum), phase only encodes spatial location in the Y direction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typically *T*E is between 5 ms and 100 ms, while *T*R is between 100 ms and 2000 ms.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] After the two-dimensional matrix (typical dimension between 128 × 128 and 512 × 512) has been acquired, producing the so-called *k*-space data, a two-dimensional inverse Fourier transform is performed to provide the familiar MR image.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Either the magnitude or phase of the Fourier transform can be taken, the former being far more common.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The magnet is the largest and most expensive component of the scanner, and the remainder of the scanner is built around it.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The strength of the magnet is measured in teslas (T).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Clinical magnets generally have a field strength in the range 0.1–3.0 T, with research systems available up to 9.4 T for human use and 21 T for animal systems.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In the United States, field strengths up to 7 T have been approved by the FDA for clinical use.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Just as important as the strength of the main magnet is its precision.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The straightness of the magnetic lines within the center (or, as it is technically known, the iso-center) of the magnet needs to be near-perfect.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Fluctuations (inhomogeneities in the field strength) within the scan region should be less than three parts per million (3 ppm).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Most superconducting magnets have their coils of superconductive wire immersed in liquid helium, inside a vessel called a cryostat.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Despite thermal insulation, sometimes including a second cryostat containing liquid nitrogen, ambient heat causes the helium to slowly boil off.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Such magnets, therefore, require regular topping-up with liquid helium.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Generally a cryocooler, also known as a coldhead, is used to recondense some helium vapor back into the liquid helium bath.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Several manufacturers now offer 'cryogenless' scanners, where instead of being immersed in liquid helium the magnet wire is cooled directly by a cryocooler.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Alternatively, the magnet may be cooled by carefully placing liquid helium in strategic spots, dramatically reducing the amount of liquid helium used, or, high temperature superconductors may be used instead.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnets are available in a variety of shapes.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, permanent magnets are most frequently C-shaped, and superconducting magnets most frequently cylindrical.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] C-shaped superconducting magnets and box-shaped permanent magnets have also been used.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Magnetic field strength is an important factor in determining image quality.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Higher magnetic fields increase signal-to-noise ratio, permitting higher resolution or faster scanning.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, higher field strengths require more costly magnets with higher maintenance costs, and have increased safety concerns.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] A field strength of 1.0–1.5 T is a good compromise between cost and performance for general medical use.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, for certain specialist uses (e.g., brain imaging) higher field strengths are desirable, with some hospitals now using 3.0 T scanners.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] When the MR scanner is placed in the hospital or clinic, its main magnetic field is far from being homogeneous enough to be used for scanning.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] That is why before doing fine tuning of the field using a sample, the magnetic field of the magnet must be measured and shimmed.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] After a sample is placed into the scanner, the main magnetic field is distorted by susceptibility boundaries within that sample, causing signal dropout (regions showing no signal) and spatial distortions in acquired images.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] For humans or animals the effect is particularly pronounced at air-tissue boundaries such as the sinuses (due to paramagnetic oxygen in air) making, for example, the frontal lobes of the brain difficult to image.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] To restore field homogeneity a set of shim coils is included in the scanner.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] These are resistive coils, usually at room temperature, capable of producing field corrections distributed as several orders of spherical harmonics.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] After placing the sample in the scanner, the *B*0 field is 'shimmed' by adjusting currents in the shim coils.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Field homogeneity is measured by examining an FID signal in the absence of field gradients.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The FID from a poorly shimmed sample will show a complex decay envelope, often with many humps.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Shim currents are then adjusted to produce a large amplitude exponentially decaying FID, indicating a homogeneous *B*0 field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Gradient coils are used to spatially encode the positions of protons by varying the magnetic field linearly across the imaging volume.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The Larmor frequency will then vary as a function of position in the *x*, *y* and *z*-axes.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Gradient coils are usually resistive electromagnets powered by sophisticated amplifiers which permit rapid and precise adjustments to their field strength and direction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typical gradient systems are capable of producing gradients from 20 to 100 mT/m (i.e., in a 1.5 T magnet, when a maximal *z*-axis gradient is applied, the field strength may be 1.45 T at one end of a 1 m-long (3.3 ft) bore and 1.55 T at the other).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] It is the magnetic gradients that determine the plane of imaging—because the orthogonal gradients can be combined freely, any plane can be selected for imaging.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Scan speed is dependent on performance of the gradient system.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Stronger gradients allow for faster imaging, or for higher resolution; similarly, gradient systems capable of faster switching can also permit faster scanning.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, gradient performance is limited by safety concerns over nerve stimulation.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Some important characteristics of gradient amplifiers and gradient coils are slew rate and gradient strength.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] As mentioned earlier, a gradient coil will create an additional, linearly varying magnetic field that adds or subtracts from the main magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This additional magnetic field will have components in all 3 directions, viz.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] *x*, *y* and *z*; however, only the component along the magnetic field (usually called the *z*-axis, hence denoted *G**z*) is useful for imaging.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Along any given axis, the gradient will add to the magnetic field on one side of the zero position and subtract from it on the other side.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Since the additional field is a gradient, it has units of gauss per centimeter or millitesla per meter (mT/m).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] High performance gradient coils used in MRI are typically capable of producing a gradient magnetic field of approximate 30 mT/m or higher for a 1.5 T MRI.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The slew rate of a gradient system is a measure of how quickly the gradients can be ramped on or off.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Typical higher performance gradients have a slew rate of up to 100–200 T·m−1·s−1.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The slew rate depends both on the gradient coil (it takes more time to ramp up or down a large coil than a small coil) and on the performance of the gradient amplifier (it takes a lot of voltage to overcome the inductance of the coil) and has significant influence on image quality.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The radio frequency (RF) transmission system consists of an RF synthesizer, power amplifier and transmitting coil.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] That coil is usually built into the body of the scanner.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The power of the transmitter is variable, but high-end whole-body scanners may have a peak output power of up to 35 kW, and be capable of sustaining average power of 1 kW.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Although these electromagnetic fields are in the RF range of tens of megahertz (often in the shortwave radio portion of the electromagnetic spectrum) at powers usually exceeding the highest powers used by amateur radio, there is very little RF interference produced by the MRI machine.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The reason for this is that the MRI is not a radio transmitter.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The RF frequency electromagnetic field produced in the "transmitting coil" is a magnetic near-field with very little associated changing electric field component (such as all conventional radio wave transmissions have).
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] The receiver consists of the coil, pre-amplifier and signal processing system.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] While it is possible to scan using the integrated coil for RF transmission and MR signal reception, if a small region is being imaged, then better image quality (i.e., higher signal-to-noise ratio) is obtained by using a close-fitting smaller coil.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] A variety of coils are available which fit closely around parts of the body such as the head, knee, wrist, breast, or internally, e.g., the rectum.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] A recent development in MRI technology has been the development of sophisticated multi-element phased array coils which are capable of acquiring multiple channels of data in parallel.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] This 'parallel imaging' technique uses unique acquisition schemes that allow for accelerated imaging, by replacing some of the spatial coding originating from the magnetic gradients with the spatial sensitivity of the different coil elements.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] However, the increased acceleration also reduces the signal-to-noise ratio and can create residual artifacts in the image reconstruction.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] Two frequently used parallel acquisition and reconstruction schemes are known as SENSE and GRAPPA.
[src:mri-physics/physics-of-magnetic-resonance-imaging] In addition, up to 8 slices can be excited simultaneously (simultaneously multislice imaging, aka multiband) which allows the TR to be reduced by the SMS acceleration; however, beyond an acceleration factor of 2, quantitative diffusion parameters are biased.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] In magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (NMR), an observable nuclear spin polarization (magnetization) is created by a homogeneous magnetic field.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] This field makes the magnetic dipole moments of the sample precess at the resonance (Larmor) frequency of the nuclei.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] At thermal equilibrium, nuclear spins precess randomly about the direction of the applied field.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] They become abruptly phase coherent when they are hit by radiofrequency (RF) pulses at the resonant frequency, created orthogonal to the field.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] The RF pulses cause the population of spin-states to be perturbed from their thermal equilibrium value.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] The generated transverse magnetization can then induce a signal in an RF coil that can be detected and amplified by an RF receiver.
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] The return of the longitudinal component of the magnetization to its equilibrium value is termed *spin-lattice* **relaxation** while the loss of phase-coherence of the spins is termed *spin-spin* relaxation, which is manifest as an observed free induction decay (FID).
[src:mri-physics/relaxation-nmr] where ΔE is the energy level difference between the two populations of spins, *k* is the Boltzmann constant, and *T* is the sample temperature.
